:Television series created by Scott Fellows]]\n[[Category:Television series produced in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Television series produced in Nova Scotia]]\n", "name_user": "MegaSmike46", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johnny_Test"}
{"title_page": "Harry Potter fandom", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Harry Potter'' fandom}}\n[[File:Long Beach Comic & Horror Con 2011 - Hogwarts students (6301701262).jpg|thumb|Fans dressed as Hogwarts students at Long Beach Comic & Horror Con 2011]]\n{{Fantasy|state=collapsed}}\n'''''Harry Potter'' fandom''' refers to the [[fandom|community of fans]] of the ''[[Harry Potter]]'' books and movies who participate in entertainment activities that revolve around the series, such as reading and writing [[fan fiction]], creating and soliciting [[fan art]], engaging in [[role-playing game]]s, socializing on ''Harry Potter''-based [[Internet forum|forums]], and more. The fandom interacts online as well as offline through activities such as [[fan convention]]s, participating in cosplay, tours of iconic landmarks relevant to the [[Harry Potter|books]] and production of the [[Harry Potter (film series)|films]], and parties held for the midnight release of each book and film.\n\nBy the fourth ''Harry Potter'' book, the legions of fans had grown so large that considerable security measures were taken to ensure that no book was purchased before the official release date.<ref name=cnn-hbp>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2005/SHOWBIZ/books/07/14/harry.potter/index.html|title=Harry Potter hits midnight frenzy|date=15 July 2005|work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=15 January 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061221021913/http://www.cnn.com/2005/SHOWBIZ/books/07/14/harry.potter/index.html |archivedate = 21 December 2006}}</ref> ''Harry Potter'' is considered one of the few [[Four-quadrant movie|four-quadrant]], multi-generation spanning franchises that exist today, despite Rowling's original marketing of the books to [[tween]]s and [[teen]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/07/20/AR2005072000038.html|title=The Magic Of 'Potter' Not Just For Kids|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=21 July 2005|first=Philip|last=Rucker|accessdate=28 February 2007}}</ref><ref name=ew-gof-midnight>{{cite news|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,276735_2,00.html|title=Wild About Harry|date=31 August 2005|accessdate=4 March 2007|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last=Fierman|first=Daniel|quote=When I buy the books for my grandchildren, I have them all gift wrapped but one...that's for me. And I haven't been 12 for over 50 years.}}</ref>\n\n==Pottermania==\n[[Image:Harry Potter lines.jpg|300px|left|thumb|''Potter'' fans wait in lines outside a [[Borders Group|Borders]] bookstore for their copy of ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]''.]]\n[[File:Harry Potter fans imitates Harry, Lumos Maxima.jpg|thumb|A fan imitates Harry casting the ''[[Magic in Harry Potter|Lumos]]'' spell]]\nPottermania is an informal term first used around 1999 describing the craze ''[[Harry Potter]]'' fans have had over the series.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.accio-quote.org/articles/1999/1099-chictimes-tucker.html|title=No end in sight for Pottermania|date=22 October 1999|accessdate=14 April 2007|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|format=reprint|last=Tucker|first=Ernest}}</ref> Fans held midnight parties to celebrate the release of the final four books at bookstores which stayed open on the night leading into the date of the release.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4191/is_20050716/ai_n14779049 |title=Midnight magic for Potter fans |date=16 July 2005 |accessdate=15 January 2007 |work=The Colorado Springs Gazette |last=Simmons |first=Matthew |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071210012715/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4191/is_20050716/ai_n14779049 |archivedate=10 December 2007 }}</ref> In 2005, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' listed the midnight release of ''[[Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire]]'' as one of \"Entertainment's Top Moments\" of the previous 25 years.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1100001,00.html|title=Entertainment's Top Moments|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=31 August 2005|accessdate=14 March 2007}}</ref>\n\nDiehard fans of the series are called \"'''Potterheads'''\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Like Magic, Muggles Make New Harry Potter Play Disappear from Bookstores |author=Ashley Ross |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/01/nyregion/harry-potter-and-the-cursed-child-disappears-from-stores.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=31 July 2016 |accessdate=13 December 2016}}</ref> Some even theme their [[weddings]] around Harry Potter. A Bridal Guide featured two real weddings soon before the release of the final movie, which quickly spread through the fandom via [[Facebook]], [[Twitter]], and [[Tumblr]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bridalguide.com/blogs/bridal-buzz/harry-potter-theme-weddings |title=Wedding Magic: Amazing Harry Potter-Themed Weddings |work=[[Bridal Guide]] |accessdate=13 July 2011 | date=29 July 2011}}</ref>\n \nThe craze over the series was referenced in [[Lauren Weisberger]]'s 2003 novel ''[[The Devil Wears Prada (novel)|The Devil Wears Prada]]'' as well as its [[The Devil Wears Prada (film)|2006 film adaptation]]. In the story, the protagonist Andrea Sachs is ordered to retrieve two copies of the next installment in the series for her boss's twins before they are published so that they can be privately flown to France, where the twins and their mother are on holiday.<ref>{{cite book|last=Weisberger|first=Lauren|authorlink=Lauren Weisberger|title=The Devil Wears Prada|year=2003|publisher=Broadway Books|location=New York City|isbn=978-0-7679-1476-5|page=[https://archive.org/details/devilwearspra00weis/page/79 79]|title-link=The Devil Wears Prada (novel)}}</ref>\n\nSome celebrities who are fans of ''Harry Potter'' include [[Lily Allen]],<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/harry-potter-20th-anniversary-jk-rowling-wizarding-world-709478/ | title='Harry Potter' at 20: Artists Reveal Tattoos, Tears, Tour Stories Inspired by the Wizarding World| date=September 2018}}</ref> [[Guillermo del Toro]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://collider.com/guillermo-del-toro-haunted-mansion-harry-potter-interview/ |title=Guillermo del Toro Talks HAUNTED MANSION and His Love of HARRY POTTER |date=7 August 2012 |first=Steve |last=Weintraub |website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref> [[Stephen King]],<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2007/07/06/harry-fans-break-out-tissues |title=Harry fans, break out the tissues! |first=Stephen |last=King |journal=Entertainment Weekly |date=6 July 2007 |accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref> [[Keira Knightley]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1595489/harry-potter-gets-love-from-robert-pattinson-lupe-fiasco-keira-knightley-and-more-celeb-fans/ |title='Harry Potter' Gets Love From Robert Pattinson, Lupe Fiasco, Keira Knightley And More Celeb Fans |date=23 September 2008 |first=Jennifer |last=Vineyard |website=MTV |accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref> [[Jennifer Lawrence]],<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.hypable.com/jennifer-lawrence-harry-potter-fan/ |title = 'The Hunger Games' Jennifer Lawrence loves 'Harry Potter'|date = 19 November 2012}}</ref> [[Evanna Lynch]], [[Liam Neeson]],<ref>http://www.contactmusic.com/pics/ld/ny_premiere_harry_potter_4_161110/liam_neeson_3100325.jpg</ref> [[Barack Obama]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1557929/Barack-Obama-under-the-Harry-Potter-spell.html |title=Barack Obama under the Harry Potter spell |date=19 July 2007 |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |first=Julian |last=Kossoff |accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref> [[Simon Pegg]],<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QgBFsI10sEA</ref> [[Seth Rogen]],<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.cinemablend.com/new/Harry-Potter-Killing-Famous-People-Seth-Rogen-Evan-Goldberg-Talk-End-36738.html?story_page=3 | title=Harry Potter and Killing Famous People: Seth Rogen and Evan Goldberg Talk This is the End| date=3 April 2013}}</ref> and [[Matt Smith (actor)|Matt Smith]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/fantastic-beasts/news/a637944/is-matt-smith-a-good-choice-for-harry-potter-spin-off-fantastic-beasts/ |title = Who would you cast in Fantastic Beasts?|date = 25 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Fan sites==\nThere are many fan web sites about ''Harry Potter'' on the Internet, the oldest ones dating to about 1997 or 1998.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.zdnet.com/2100-9595_22-503255.html|date=20 December 2000|accessdate=2 January 2007|publisher=Wall Street Journal|format=reprint|title=Warner Bros. claims Harry Potter sites|last=Grunier|first=Stephanie|author2=John Lippman |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061116075618/http://news.zdnet.com/2100-9595_22-503255.html |archivedate = 16 November 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/general/googleeyed-over-harry/2005/07/15/1121429358851.html?oneclick=true|publisher=[[The Age]]|title=Google-eyed over Harry|date=16 July 2005|first=Jo|last=Chandler|accessdate=28 February 2007 | location=Melbourne}}</ref><ref name=the-star-sites>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/artsentertainment/article/201974|title=Potter sites wild about Harry|date=11 April 2007|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]|accessdate=13 April 2007|last=Italie|first=Hillel}}</ref> [[J. K. Rowling]] has an open relationship with her fan base, and since 2004 periodically hands out a \"fan site award\" on her official web site.<ref name=fansites-main>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite.cfm|last=Rowling|first=J. K.|title=Section: Fan Sites|work=J. K. Rowling Official Site|accessdate=2 January 2007|authorlink=J. K. Rowling|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061230195904/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite.cfm|archivedate=30 December 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The first site to receive the award was Immeritus, a fan site mostly devoted to [[Sirius Black]], and about which Rowling wrote, \"I am so proud of the fact that a character, whom I always liked very much, though he never appeared as much more than a brooding presence in the books, has gained a passionate fan-club.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=1|last=Rowling|first=J. K.|title=Section: Fan Sites: Immeritus|work=J. K. Rowling Official Site|accessdate=2 January 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110623034807/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=1|archivedate=23 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, after Immeritus, Rowling bestowed the honour upon four sites. The first was Godric's Hollow;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hp-lexicon.org/about/sources/jkr.com/jkr-com-timeline.html|title=J. K. Rowling Official Site: Timeline|work=[[The Harry Potter Lexicon]]|accessdate=2 January 2006}}</ref> for some time however, the site's domain name was occupied by advertisers and its content was lost<ref>{{cite web|url=http://godricshollow.org/|title=Godricshollow.org|accessdate=9 January 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060104212857/http://www.godricshollow.org/|archivedate=4 January 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and there is no further record on Rowling's site that Godric's Hollow ever received the award,<ref name=fansites-main/> although in 2010 the website came back online again albeit with a lot of content missing. The next site was the [[Harry Potter Lexicon]], an online encyclopedia Rowling has admitted to visiting while writing away from home rather than buying a copy of her books in a store. She called it \"for the dangerously obsessive; my natural home.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=14|last=Rowling|first=J. K.|accessdate=2 January 2006|work=J. K. Rowling Official Site|title=Section: Fan Sites: The Harry Potter Lexicon|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060316220934/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=14|archivedate=16 March 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The third site of 2004 was [[MuggleNet]], a web site featuring the latest news in the Potter world, among editorials, forums, and a podcast. Rowling wrote when giving the award, \"It's high time I paid homage to the mighty MuggleNet,\" and listed all the features she loved, including \"the pretty-much-exhaustive information on all books and films.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=15|last=Rowling|first=J. K.|title=Section: Fan Sites: MuggleNet|work=J. K. Rowling Official Site|accessdate=2 January 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061206023706/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=15|archivedate=6 December 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The last site was [[HPANA]], the first fan site Rowling ever visited, \"faster off the mark with Harry Potter news than any other site\" Rowling knows, and \"fantastically user-friendly.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=16 |last=Rowling |first=J. K. |title=Section: Fan Sites: HPANA |work=J. K. Rowling Official Site |accessdate=2 January 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060216183428/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=16 |archivedate=16 February 2006 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, only [[The Leaky Cauldron (website)|The Leaky Cauldron]] was honored. In Rowling's words, \"it is about the worst kept secret on this website that I am a huge fan of The Leaky Cauldron,\" which she calls a \"wonderfully well designed mine of accurate information on all things Harry Potter.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=17|last=Rowling|first=J. K.|title=Section: Fan Sites: The Leaky Cauldron|work=J. K. Rowling Official Site|accessdate=2 January 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061209064200/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=17|archivedate=9 December 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On another occasion, Rowling has called the Leaky Cauldron her \"favourite fan site.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/static_downloads/jkr-ootp-rah.mp3 |title=JKR at Royal Albert Hall |date=26 June 2003 |publisher=The Leaky Cauldron |last=Rowling |first=J. K. |accessdate=9 January 2007 |format=QuickTime |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070704083555/http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/static_downloads/jkr-ootp-rah.mp3 |archivedate=4 July 2007 }}</ref> In 2006, the Brazilian website Potterish was the only site honoured, in recognition of its \"style, [its] Potter-expertise and [its] responsible reporting.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=18|last=Rowling|first=J. K.|title=Section: Fan Sites: Potterish.com|work=J. K. Rowling Official Site|accessdate=2 January 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070118084800/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=18|archivedate=18 January 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2007, [[Harry Potter Fan Zone]] received the award. Rowling recognized the insightful editorials as well as praised the site for its young and dedicated staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=19|last=Rowling|first=J. K.|title=Section: Fan Sites: Harry Potter Fan Zone.com|work=J. K. Rowling Official Site|accessdate=10 May 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070514034127/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=19|archivedate=14 May 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In December 2007, the award went to The Harry Potter Alliance, a campaign that seeks to end discrimination, genocide, poverty, AIDS, global warming, and other \"real-world Dark Arts\", relating these problems to the books. Rowling called the project \"extraordinary\" and \"most inspirational\", and paralleled its mission to \"the values for which Dumbledore's Army fought in the books\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=20|last=Rowling|first=J. K.|title=Section: Fan Sites: The HP Alliance|work=J. K. Rowling Official Site|accessdate=2 January 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080101171647/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=20|archivedate=1 January 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In an article about her in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', Rowling expressed her gratefulness at the site's successful work raising awareness and sign-up levels among anti-genocide coalitions.<ref name=jkr-time-dec-2007>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/personoftheyear/article/0,28804,1690753_1695388_1695436,00.html|title=J.K. Rowling|last=Gibbs|first=Nancy|publisher=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=2 January 2008|date=31 December 2007}}</ref>\n\nAt one time, [[Warner Bros.]], which owns the rights to ''Harry Potter'' and its affiliates, tried to shut down the sites. The unsuccessful attempt eventually led to their inviting the webmasters of the top sites to premieres of the films and tours of the film sets, because of their close connection with the fans. Warner Bros. executives have acknowledged that many fans are disappointed that certain elements of the books are left out, but not trying to avoid criticism, \"bringing the fan sites into the process is what we feel is really important.\"<ref name=the-star-sites/>\n\nThese fan sites contain news updates into the world of the [[Harry Potter|books]], [[Harry Potter (film)|films]], and [[List of Harry Potter films cast members|film cast members]] through the use of forums, image galleries, or video galleries.<ref>{{cite web|last=Anelli|first=Melissa|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/#static:sitefaq|title=A Brief (Believe it or Not) History of the Leaky Cauldron|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron|accessdate=3 January 2007}}</ref> They also host user-submitted creations, such as [[fan art]] or fan fiction.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/index.php?articleID=9355|title=Fan Art Contest&nbsp;\u2014 Design a \"Deathly Hallows\" Book Cover|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron|date=23 December 2006|accessdate=3 January 2007|last=Tynion|first=Julie}}</ref>\n\n===Podcasts===\n<!--A [[podcast]] is a media file that is distributed by unpaid subscription over the [[Internet]] using [[Web syndication|syndication]] [[Web feed|feeds]], for playback on mobile devices and [[personal computer]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://technology.guardian.co.uk/weekly/story/0,16376,1683937,00.html|title=Short shrift|date=2006-01-12|accessdate=2007-01-21|publisher=The Guardian|last=Arthur|first=Charles and Jack Schofield | location=London}}</ref>-->\nThe Harry Potter fandom has embraced [[podcast]]s as a regular, often weekly, insight to the latest discussion in the fandom. [[Apple Inc.]] has featured two of the podcasts, [[MuggleCast]] and [[PotterCast]].<ref name=apple-enews>{{cite news|url=https://www.apple.com/enews/2005/09/08enews1.html |title=Book corner: Secrets of Podcasting |date=8 September 2005 |accessdate=31 January 2007 |publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051227152737/http://www.apple.com/enews/2005/09/08enews1.html |archivedate=27 December 2005 |df=dmy }}</ref> Both have reached the top spot of [[iTunes]] podcast rankings and have been polled one of the top 50 favorite podcasts.<ref name=pr-newswire-mc>{{cite news|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/cgi-bin/stories.pl?ACCT=104&STORY=/www/story/11-08-2005/0004210790&EDATE=|title=Mugglenet.com Taps Limelight's Magic for Podcast Delivery of Harry Potter Content|date=8 November 2005|accessdate=31 January 2007|publisher=PR Newswire}}</ref> At the 2006 Podcast Awards, when MuggleCast and PotterCast each received two nominations for the same two categories, the two podcasts teamed up and requested listeners vote for PotterCast in the Best Entertainment category and MuggleCast in the People's Choice category. Both podcasts won these respective categories.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/index.php?articleID=8970|title=PotterCast Voted Best Entertainment Podcast at Podcast Awards|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron|date=15 August 2006|accessdate=27 February 2007|last=Anelli|first=Melissa}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://mugglenet.com/app/news/full_story/370 |title=MuggleCast wins People's Choice Award |date=2 October 2006 |accessdate=27 February 2007 |publisher=MuggleNet |last=Sims |first=Andrew |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061203022310/http://mugglenet.com/app/news/full_story/370 |archivedate=3 December 2006 }}</ref>\n\nMuggleCast, hosted by [[MuggleNet]] staffers, was created in August 2005, not long after the release of ''Half-Blood Prince''.<ref name=mugglecast-about>{{cite web|url=http://www.mugglenet.com/mugglecast/index.php?page=about.php|title=MuggleCast: About|accessdate=31 January 2007|publisher=MuggleCast}}</ref> Topics of the first show focused on [[Horcrux]]es, \"[[Death Eater#Regulus Black|R.A.B.]]\", the [[Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire (film)|''Goblet of Fire'' film]], which was due for release two months later, and the website DumbledoreIsNotDead.com.<ref name=mc-episode1-transcript>{{cite news|url=http://www.mugglenet.com/mugglecast/index.php?page=transcripts/1.php|date=7 August 2005|accessdate=31 January 2007|publisher=MuggleCast|title=MuggleCast EP1 Transcript}}</ref> Since then, MuggleCast has held chapter-by-chapter discussions, character analyses, and a discussion on a \"theory of the week\". MuggleCast has also added humour to their podcast with segments like \"Spy on Spartz,\" where the hosts would call MuggleNet webmaster Emerson Spartz and reveal his current location or activity with the listening audience. British staff member Jamie Lawrence tells a British joke of the week, and host Andrew Sims reads an email sent to MuggleNet with a strange request or incoherent talk (dubbed \"Huh?! Email of the Week\").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mugglenet.com/mugglecast/index.php?page=episodes_page1.php|title=MuggleCast Episodes 1 - 10|publisher=MuggleCast|accessdate=27 February 2007}}</ref> MuggleCast is currently the highest rated Harry Potter Podcast on the Internet. The MuggleCast website will continue to serve as a resource for other Harry Potter fans who want to rediscover the show.\n\nPotterCast was released less than two weeks after MuggleCast's first episode. Produced by [[The Leaky Cauldron (website)|The Leaky Cauldron]], it differed from MuggleCast with a more structured program, including various segments and involvement of more people on the Leaky Cauldron staff compared to MuggleCast. It also was the first Potter podcast to produce regular interviews with people directly involved with the books and films. The first show featured interviews with [[Stuart Craig]], art director of the films, as well as [[Bonnie Wright]], who plays [[Ginny Weasley]]. PotterCast has also interviewed [[Matthew Lewis (actor)|Matthew Lewis]] (the actor who portrays [[Neville Longbottom]]), [[Evanna Lynch]] ([[Luna Lovegood]]), [[Jamie Waylett]] ([[Vincent Crabbe]]), [[Rupert Grint]] ([[Ron Weasley]]), [[Chris Columbus (filmmaker)|Chris Columbus]], [[Alfonso Cuar\u00f3n]], [[Mike Newell (director)|Mike Newell]] (directors of the first four films), Arthur A. Levine and Cheryl Klein (editors of the books at [[Scholastic Corporation|Scholastic]]), and Rowling herself.<ref name=what-is-pc>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/pottercast/page/what|title=PotterCast is the Harry Potter podcast brought to you by The Leaky Cauldron|publisher=PotterCast|accessdate=27 February 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070102134107/http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/pottercast/page/what |archivedate = 2 January 2007|date=19 September 2002}}</ref>\n\nThe two sites are friendly rivals and have aired several combined episodes, which they call \"The Leaky Mug\", a separate podcast released on a separate feed from time to time. Live joint podcasts have been held in [[New York City]], [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]], and [[California]]. From time to time, hosts on one podcast will appear on their counterpart.<ref name=what-is-pc/>\n\nOther notable Harry Potter podcasts include ''[[Harry Potter and the Sacred Text]]'', in which the books are read as if they were a religious text, ''Witch Please'', which looks at the books through a feminist lens, and ''Potterotica'', in which actors read Harry Potter fan fiction aloud.<ref>{{cite web |title=Harry Potter podcasts that even muggles can love |url=https://www.cbc.ca/radio/podcastplaylist/harry-potter-podcasts-that-even-muggles-can-love-1.3992234 |website=[[CBC Radio]] |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Ragsdale |first1=Melissa |title=11 Harry Potter Podcasts Every Potterhead Needs In Their Life |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/11-harry-potter-podcasts-every-potterhead-needs-in-their-life-62902 |website=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Fan fiction==\nRowling has backed [[fan fiction]] stories on the Internet, stories written by fans that involve [[Harry Potter (character)|Harry Potter]] or other characters in the books.<ref name=fanfic-bbc>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3753001.stm|title=Rowling backs Potter fan fiction|work=BBC|date=27 May 2004|accessdate=14 January 2007 | first=Darren | last=Waters}}</ref> A March 2007 study showed that \"Harry Potter\" is the most searched-for fan fiction subject online.<ref name=most-searched-fanfiction>{{cite news|url=http://buzz.yahoo.com/buzzlog/67161/fantastic-fiction |title=Fantastic Fiction |date=20 March 2007 |accessdate=7 April 2007 |last=Hurd |first=Gordon |work=[[Yahoo!]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071222003119/http://buzz.yahoo.com/buzzlog/67161/fantastic-fiction |archivedate=22 December 2007 }}</ref> Some fans will use canon established in the books to write stories of past and future events in the ''Harry Potter'' world; others write stories that have little relation to the books other than the characters' names and the settings in which the fan fiction takes place. On [[FanFiction.Net]], there are over 817,000, while [[Archive of Our Own]] has  over 230,000 stories on Harry Potter {{As of|2020|4|lc=y|df=US}}. There are numerous websites devoted solely to Harry Potter fan fiction. Of these, according to rankings on Alexa.com, HarryPotterFanfiction.com has grown to be the most popular.\n\nA well-known work of fan fiction is The Shoebox Project, created by two [[LiveJournal]] users. Over 8500 people subscribe to the story so that they are alerted when new posts update the story. The authors' works, including this project, were featured in an article in ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' discussing the growth in popularity of fandoms.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/public/article/SB115836001321164886.html|title=Rewriting the Rules of Fiction|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|date=16 September 2007|accessdate=4 September 2007|last=Jurgensen|first=John}}</ref>\n\nThe current most reviewed piece of fanfiction, with over 25,000 reviews, is ''[[Harry Potter and the Methods of Rationality]]'' by [[Eliezer Yudkowsky]] writing under the pseudonym of Less Wrong.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fanfiction.net/s/5782108/1/Harry_Potter_and_the_Methods_of_Rationality |title=Harry Potter and the Methods of Rationality Chapter 1: A Day of Very Low Probability, a harry potter fanfic |publisher=FanFiction.Net |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://esr.ibiblio.org/?p=2100 |title=Harry Potter and the Methods of Rationality |publisher=Esr.ibiblio.org |date=6 July 2010 |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, the \"popular 'bad' fanfic\" ''[[My Immortal (fan fiction)|My Immortal]]'' was posted on [[FanFiction.Net]] by user \"Tara Gilesbie\".<ref name=\"guide\">{{cite book |title= The Ultimate Guide to the Harry Potter Fandom|last= Pyne|first= Erin |year= 2010|publisher= What The Flux Comics Publishing Inc. |isbn= 978-1-4507-4560-4|page= 126}}</ref><ref name=\"cracked\">{{cite web|url = http://www.cracked.com/funny-3085-my-immortal/|title=My Immortal|publisher= [[Cracked.com]]|accessdate = 9 May 2011}}</ref> It was deleted by the site's administrators in 2008,<ref name=\"cracked\"/> but not before amassing over eight thousand negative reviews.<ref name=\"guide\"/> It spawned a number of [[YouTube]] spoofs<ref name=\"guide\"/> and a number of imitators created \"sequels\" claiming to be the original Tara.<ref name=\"cracked\"/>\n\nIn 2007, a web-based novel, ''[[James Potter and the Hall of Elders' Crossing]]'', was written by a computer animator named George Lippert. The book was written as a supplement to fill the void after ''Deathly Hallows'', and received eventual approval from Rowling herself.<ref name=gnorm>{{cite web|title=On Eve of James Potter Sequel, Harry Potter fan Fiction Heats up: Unlikely Author Poised to Keep the Story Alive|publisher=PRWEB|year=2008|url=http://www.prweb.com/releases/2008/07/prweb1080574.htm|accessdate=20 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nRowling has said, \"I find it very flattering that people love the characters that much.\" She has adopted a positive position on fan fiction, unlike authors such as [[Anne McCaffrey]] or [[Anne Rice]] who discourage fans from writing about their books and have asked sites like FanFiction.Net to remove all stories of their works, requests honored by the site.<ref name=fanfic-bbc/> However, Rowling has been \"alarmed by pornographic or sexually explicit material clearly not meant for kids,\" according to Neil Blair, an attorney for her publisher. The attorneys have sent [[cease and desist]] letters to sites that host adult material.<ref name=fanfic-hpana>{{cite news|url=http://www.hpana.com/news.14252.html|title=Potter fans produce Potter fiction|publisher=HPANA|date=18 June 2003|accessdate=14 January 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060811000252/http://www.hpana.com/news.14252.html|archive-date=11 August 2006|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nPotter fan fiction also has a large following in the [[slash fiction]] genre, stories which feature sexual relationships that do not exist in the books (''[[Shipping (fandom)|shipping]]''), often portraying homosexual pairings.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://technology.guardian.co.uk/online/story/0,,853539,00.html|title=Fan fiction|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=5 December 2002|accessdate=14 January 2007|last=Pauli|first=Michelle | location=London}}</ref><ref name=potter-slash>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.om/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/chronicle/archive/2001/11/18/IN92578.DTL |page=D3 |title=Pottershots: The trouble with Harry |last=Noxon |first=Christopher |date=18 November 2001 |accessdate=14 April 2007 |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Famous pairings include Harry with [[Draco Malfoy]] or [[Cedric Diggory]], and [[Remus Lupin]] with [[Sirius Black]].<ref name=potter-slash/><ref name=observer-lumos>{{cite news|url=http://books.guardian.co.uk/departments/childrenandteens/story/0,,1838086,00.html|title=Harry Potter and the mystery of an academic obsession|date=6 August 2006|accessdate=27 July 2007|work=The Guardian|last=Cadwalladr|first=Carole | location=London}}</ref> Harry Potter slash has eroded some of the antipathy towards underage sexuality in the wider slash fandom.<ref name=\"WorldofYaoi\">McLelland, Mark. [http://ro.uow.edu.au/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1152&context=artspapers The World of Yaoi: The Internet, Censorship and the Global \u201cBoys\u2019 Love\u201d Fandom] ''[[The Australian Feminist Law Journal]]'', 2005.</ref>\n\nTracey \"T\" Proctor, a moderator of FictionAlley.org, a ''Harry Potter'' fanfiction website, said 'I don't really get into the children's aspect of it, but rather the teachers, the adult characters. I read someone once who said, \"If she didn't want us fantasizing about her characters, she needs to stop having these handsome men portraying them.\" And that's the truth: It's very hard not to look at Alan Rickman [Professor Severus Snape] and Jason Isaacs [Lucius Malfoy] and not get erotic thoughts. I have some fan fiction at Fiction Alley. You want to write stories about the characters that J.K. is not writing, about their love lives that you don't see in the book.'<ref>\"Petrosexuals.\" ''[[Riverfront Times]]''. 4 January 2006. p. [http://www.riverfronttimes.com/2006-01-04/news/petrosexuals/ 1]. Retrieved on 19 February 2013.</ref>\n\nIn November 2006, [[Jason Isaacs]], who plays [[Lucius Malfoy]] in the ''Potter'' films, said that he had read fan fiction about his character and gets \"a huge kick out of the more far-out stuff.\"<ref name=isaacs-hp-lex>{{cite news|url=http://www.hp-lexicon.org/about/films/lex-op-set-teaser.html|title=The Lexicon Visits The Magic Factory (part one)|date=24 November 2006|accessdate=14 January 2007|publisher=The [[Harry Potter Lexicon]]|last=VanderArk|first=Steve|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070113125007/http://www.hp-lexicon.org/about/films/lex-op-set-teaser.html|archivedate=13 January 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Discussion===\nPrior to the publication of ''[[Deathly Hallows]]'', much of the energy of the Potter fandom was devoted to speculation and debate about upcoming plot and character developments. To this end, clues from the earlier books and deliberate hints from [[J. K. Rowling]] (in interviews and on her website) were heavily scrutinised by fans. In particular, fan essays were published on websites such as [[Mugglenet]] (the \"world famous editorials\"), the [[Harry Potter Lexicon]] and [[The Leaky Cauldron (website)|The Leaky Cauldron]] (Scribbulus project) among others: offering theories, comment and analysis on all aspects of the series. The [[Yahoo]] discussion list [[Harry Potter for Grown Ups]] (founded in 1999) is also noteworthy for its detailed criticism and discussion of the Harry Potter books.\n\nSpeculation intensified with the July 2005 publication of ''[[Half-Blood Prince]]'' and the detailed post-publication interview given by Rowling to Mugglenet and The Leaky Cauldron.<ref>{{cite web|author=MuggleNet |url=http://www.mugglenet.com/jkrinterview.shtml |title=Emerson and Melissa's J.K. Rowling Interview Page 1 |publisher=MuggleNet |accessdate=16 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120612094057/http://www.mugglenet.com/jkrinterview.shtml |archivedate=12 June 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> Notably, DumbledoreIsNotDead.com sought to understand the events of the sixth book in a different way. (Rowling later confirmed, however&nbsp;\u2013 on 2 August 2006&nbsp;\u2013 that Dumbledore was, in fact, dead, humorously apologising to the website as she did so.)<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.hpana.com/news.19531.html | title=Dumbledore 'definitely' dead, says Rowling| date=3 August 2006}}</ref> A collection of essays, ''Who Killed Albus Dumbledore?: What Really Happened in Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince? Six Expert Harry Potter Detectives Examine the Evidence'', was published by Zossima Press in November 2006. Contributors included the Christian author [[John Granger]] and Joyce Odell of Red Hen Publications, whose own website contains numerous essays on the Potterverse and fandom itself.\n\nIn 2006, in advance of the arrival of the seventh Potter novel, five MuggleNet staff members co-authored the reference book ''Mugglenet.Com's What Will Happen in Harry Potter 7: Who Lives, Who Dies, Who Falls in Love and How Will the Adventure Finally End'', an anthology of unofficial fan predictions; while early in 2007, Leaky launched HarryPotterSeven.com, featuring \"roundups and predictions from some of the most knowledgeable fans online\" (including [[Steve Vander Ark]] of the Lexicon). Late additions to the fan scene (prior to the publication of ''[[Deathly Hallows]]'') included BeyondHogwarts.com (the successor to DumbledoreIsNotDead.com), which billed itself as \"the only ongoing online Harry Potter fan conference\", as well as Book7.co.uk, which offered a hypothetical \"evidence-based synopsis\" of the seventh novel. To this day, debate and reaction to the novels and films continues on web forums (including Mugglenet's Chamber of Secrets community and TLC's Leaky Lounge).\n\n==Fan film and television==\n{{main|Voldemort: Origins of the Heir}}\nA 2018 Italian fan-made [[prequel]] to the series, ''[[Voldemort: Origins of the Heir]]'', depicts the story of Tom Riddle's rise to power.<ref name=Echites2018>{{Cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/spettacoli/cinema/2018/01/16/news/voldemort-186609861/?ref=RHPPRT-BS-I0-C4-P1-S1.4-T1|title= CINEMA Le origini di Voldemort in un film tutto italiano|last=Echites|first=Giulia|work=[[Repubblica.it]]|access-date=17 January 2018|date=16 January 2018|language=it-IT}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/0/voldemort-origins-heir-review-fun-free-harry-potter-fan-film/|title=Voldemort: Origins of the Heir review: a fun-free Harry Potter fan film lifted by magical effects|last=Brown|first=Kat|date=2018|work=The Telegraph|access-date=21 January 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> The teaser trailer was released on in June 2017, receiving exceeded thirty million views in less than 48 hours on Facebook. The full movie was later released on YouTube on 13 January 2018, receiving over twelve million views in ten days.\n\n''[[Hermione Granger and the Quarter Life Crisis]]'' is an online TV series focused on Hermione Granger's life after Hogwarts.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.elle.com/uk/life-and-culture/culture/news/a33603/hermione-granger-quarter-life-crisis/|title=The side of Hermione you didn't get to see|date=2017-01-24|work=ELLE|access-date=2018-11-21|language=en-GB}}</ref> In the show, Granger, cast as a black woman played by Ashley Romans,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shadowandact.com/web-series-hermione-granger-and-the-quarter-life-crisis/|title='Hermione Granger and the Quarter Life Crisis' centers a black Hermione in a post-Hogwarts world|website=shadowandact.com|language=en|access-date=2018-11-21}}</ref> has broken up with Ron Weasley and moved to Los Angeles to reevaluate her life and choices.\n\n==Conventions==\n[[File:Sectus-midnight-wait.jpg|thumb|right|260px|Attendees of Sectus convention in London await the midnight release of ''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows'']]\n[[Fan conventions]] have been another way that the fandom has congregated. Conventions such as Prophecy, [[Mischief Management|LeakyCon]], Infinitus, Azkatraz, and Ascendio have maintained an academic emphasis, hosting professional keynote speakers as well as keeping the atmosphere playful and friendly. They have featured prominent members of the fandom such as Jennie Levine, owner of SugarQuill.net (Phoenix Rising, 2007); Melissa Anelli, current webmaster of The Leaky Cauldron (Phoenix Rising, 2007; Leakycon, 2009/2011/2012); Sue Upton, former Senior Editor of the Leaky Cauldron (Prophecy, 2007); Heidi Tandy, founder of Fiction Alley (Prophecy, 2007), Paul and Joe DeGeorge of the wizard rock band [[Harry and the Potters]] (along with several other more well-known Wizard Rock bands such as The Remus Lupins, The Parselmouths, Ministry of Magic, and The Whomping Willows) (see [[#Wizard rock|below]])<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/?articleID=9786|date=1 May 2007|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron|title=Prophecy Announces Keynote Speakers|last=Anelli|first=Melissa|accessdate=1 May 2007}}</ref> (Prophecy, 2007; Leakycon, 2009/2011/2012), Andrew Slack, founder of The [[Harry Potter Alliance]], and [[StarKid Productions|StarKid]], the cast of the fan made musicals \"A Very Potter Musical\", \"A Very Potter Sequel\", and \"A Very Potter Senior Year\".\n\nStill, the conventions try to attract the fandom with other fun-filled ''Potter''-centric activities, often more interactive, such as wizarding chess, water [[Quidditch]], a showing of the [[Harry Potter (film)|''Harry Potter'' films]],<ref name=lumos-events>{{cite web|url=http://lumos2006.org/schedule.shtml|title=Lumos 2006: Programming&nbsp;\u2014 Schedule|accessdate=3 January 2007|publisher=Lumos 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070209135552/http://lumos2006.org/schedule.shtml|archivedate=9 February 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> or local cultural immersions. Live podcasts are often recorded during these events,<ref>{{cite web|title=MuggleCast Episodes 234 & 235 |url=http://www.mugglenet.com/mugglecast/episodes_page17.php |work=MuggleCast |publisher=MuggleNet |accessdate=12 December 2012 |date=18 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130227081228/http://www.mugglenet.com/mugglecast/episodes_page17.php |archivedate=27 February 2013 }}</ref> and live Wizard Rock shows have become a fairly large part of recent conventions.<ref>{{cite web|last=Anelli|first=Melissa|title=LeakyCon 2011 Announces Wizard Rock Lineup|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/2010/10/5/leakycon-2011-announces-wizard-rock-lineup|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron|accessdate=12 December 2012|date=5 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ascendio Wrocks! |url=http://hp2012.org/?page_id=837 |publisher=Ascendio 2012/HPEF |accessdate=6 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120417130540/http://hp2012.org/?page_id=837 |archivedate=17 April 2012 }}</ref> Members of the ''Harry Potter'' cast have been brought in for the conferences; actors such as [[Evanna Lynch]] (Luna Lovegood) and [[Chris Rankin|Christopher Rankin]] (Percy Weasley), along with several others, have appeared to give live Q&A sessions and keynote presentations about the series.<ref>{{cite web|last=Anelli|first=Melissa|title=Meet the Deathly Hallows Actors at Leakycon 2011|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/2011/6/2/meet-the-new-potter-actors-at-leakycon-2011|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron|accessdate=12 December 2012|date=2 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to fandom-specific programming, LeakyCon 2011 and 2012 have hosted LitDays (as well as incorporating the many fandoms ''Harry Potter'' fans have branched into since the ending of the series). LitDays are full of programming with authors, agents, and editors. A few key examples are [[John Green (author)|John Green]], author of the award-winning young adult novels ''[[The Fault in Our Stars]]'' and ''[[Looking for Alaska]]''; [[Scott Westerfeld]], author of the ''Uglies'' series and ''Leviathan''; and [[David Levithan]], author of ''Nick & Norah's Infinite Playlist'' and ''The Lover's Dictionary''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leakycon 2011 Programming|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/leakycon/leakycon2011programming.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626032840/http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/leakycon/leakycon2011programming.pdf |archivedate=2011-06-26|accessdate=12 December 2012|pages=2\u20134}}</ref>\n\nThese conventions are now incorporating the recently opened theme park The Wizarding World of Harry Potter<ref>{{cite web|title=The Wizarding World of Harry Potter|url=http://www.universalorlando.com/harrypotter/|accessdate=12 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121211184519/http://www.universalorlando.com/HarryPotter/|archive-date=11 December 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> into their itinerary, built inside Universal's Island of Adventure in Orlando, Florida. At the ''Harry Potter'' fan conventions Infinitus 2010,<ref>{{cite web|last=Brigante|first=Ricky|title=Night of a Thousand Wizards draws biggest Harry Potter fans to Universal Orlando's Wizarding World at Infinitus 2010|url=http://www.insidethemagic.net/2010/07/night-of-a-thousand-wizards-draws-biggest-harry-potter-fans-to-universal-orlandos-wizarding-world-at-infinitus-2010/|accessdate=12 December 2012|date=23 July 2010}}</ref> LeakyCon 2011,<ref>{{cite web|title=Leakycon 2011 Programming |url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/leakycon/leakycon2011programming.pdf |publisher=The-Leaky-Cauldron.org |accessdate=6 December 2012 |page=5 |year=2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626032840/http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/leakycon/leakycon2011programming.pdf |archivedate=26 June 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Roseboom|first=Matt|title=Wizarding World of Harry Potter Will be 'Open at the Close' for a Special Fan Event|url=http://attractionsmagazine.com/blog/2011/05/16/wizarding-world-of-harry-potter-will-be-open-at-the-close-for-special-fan-event/|accessdate=12 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126053342/http://attractionsmagazine.com/blog/2011/05/16/wizarding-world-of-harry-potter-will-be-open-at-the-close-for-special-fan-event/|archive-date=26 January 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and Ascendio 2012,<ref>{{cite web|title=Night of A Thousand Wizards 2 |url=http://hp2012.org/?page_id=864 |publisher=Ascendio 2012 |accessdate=6 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121007181615/http://hp2012.org/?page_id=864 |archivedate=7 October 2012 }}</ref> special events were held at the theme park dedicated to the series. These are after-hours events for convention attendees who purchased tickets to experience and explore the park by themselves. The event included talks given by creators of the park, free food and [[butterbeer]], and live wizard rock shows inside the park.\n\n==Festivals==\nIn addition to conventions, Harry Potter fandom has further expanded to town festivals, including the Chestertown Harry Potter Festival (Maryland),<ref>{{cite web|title=Chestertown Harry Potter Festival |url=http://chestertownhpfest.org/|accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> the Chestnut Hill Harry Potter Festival (Philadelphia),<ref>{{cite web|title=Chestnut HIll Harry Potter Festival|url=http://chestnuthillpa.com/events/harry-potter-festival-2016/|accessdate=15 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160912173458/http://chestnuthillpa.com/events/harry-potter-festival-2016/|archivedate=12 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  Edgerton's Harry Potter Festival (Wisconsin),<ref>{{cite web|title=Edgerton's Harry Potter Festival|url=http://www.harrypotterfestival.com/|accessdate=15 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160712122715/http://www.harrypotterfestival.com/|archive-date=12 July 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and the Spellbound Festival (Michigan, 2016; Ontario, 2018; New York, 2019),<ref>{{cite web|title=Spellbound Festival |url=http://stbonavenue.com/spellbound-festival/|accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> among others.\n\n==Religions==\nThe Harry Potter fandom has also led to the development of at least one religion. The religion of 'Snapeism' was active from 2005-2011. The Snapists (popularly known as the Snapewives) worshipped the Severus Snape character.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Alderton|first1=Zoe|title='Snapewives' and 'Snapeism': A Fiction-Based Religion within the Harry Potter Fandom|journal=Religions|date=3 March 2014|volume=5|issue=1|pages=219\u2013267|doi=10.3390/rel5010219|doi-access=free}}</ref> The Snapists were mocked by the majority of the fandom, especially the JournalFen community 'fandom_wank', for their unorthodox belief systems. Nevertheless, recent scholarship has argued for the validity of fandom faiths.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Davidsen|first1=Markus A.|title=Fiction-Based Religion: Conceptualising a New Category Against History-Based Religion and Fandom|journal=Culture and Religion|volume=14|issue=4|pages=378\u2013395|doi=10.1080/14755610.2013.838798|year=2013|url=https://openaccess.leidenuniv.nl/bitstream/handle/1887/48123/Davidsen2013ConceptualisingFiction-basedReligion_Postprint.pdf?sequence=1}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Cusack|first1=Carole|title=Invented Religions: Imagination, Fiction and Faith|date=2010|publisher=Ashgate|location=Farnham}}</ref>\n\nThe Snapists exist within a context of 'canon scepticism' - the belief that Rowling is a flawed interpreter of the Harry Potter universe who misrepresents the objective reality of certain characters and plot developments.<ref name=\"Alderton Snapewives\">{{cite journal|last1=Alderton|first1=Zoe|title='Snapewives' and 'Snapeism': A Fiction-Based Religion within the Harry Potter Fandom|journal=Religions|date=3 March 2014|volume=5|issue=1|page=224|doi=10.3390/rel5010219|doi-access=free}}</ref> The Snapists believe that Rowling has misinterpreted Snape and disrespected him as a character. They also feel that Snape can contact them and provide them with help and guidance in life.\n\n==\"Ship debates\"==\n{{further|Shipping (fandom)#Harry Potter fandom}}\nIn the fandom the word \"ship\" and its derivatives like \"shipping\" or \"shipper\" are commonly used as shorthand for the word \"relationship.\"\n\nThe ''Harry Potter'' series generated ship debates with supporters of the prospective relationship between [[Harry Potter (character)|Harry Potter]] and his close female friend [[Hermione Granger]] at odds with supporters of Hermione ending up instead with [[Ron Weasley]], close friend of both, as well as  supporters of Harry ending up with [[Ginny Weasley]], Ron's younger sister.\n\nQuotes from Rowling which seemed to contradict the possibility of Harry ending up with Hermione were usually countered by claiming them to be deliberate obfuscations designed to lure astute observation off-course (though such claims were far from undisputed, given that these allegedly vague quotes included such phrases as \"[Harry and Hermione] are very platonic friends\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accio-quote.org/articles/1999/1099-pressclubtransc.htm |title=1999: Accio Quote!, the largest archive of J.K. Rowling interviews on the web |publisher=Accio-quote.org |date=20 October 1999 |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref> and were repeated on at least three different occasions).\n\nAn interview with J.K. Rowling conducted by fansite webmasters Emerson Spartz ([[MuggleNet]]) and Melissa Anelli ([[The Leaky Cauldron (website)|The Leaky Cauldron]]) shortly after the book's release turned out to be quite controversial. During the interview Spartz commented that Harry/Hermione shippers were \"delusional\", to which Rowling chuckled, though making it clear that she did not share the sentiment and that the Harry/Hermione fans were \"still valued members of her readership\". This incident resulted in an uproar among Harry/Hermione shippers. The uproar was loud enough to merit an article in the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]''.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2005/08/03/DDG0RE1DDI1.DTL | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | first=Neva | last=Chonin | title=If you're an obsessed Harry Potter fan, Voldemort isn't the problem. It's Hermione versus Ginny | date=24 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nRowling's attitude towards the shipping phenomenon has varied between amused and bewildered to frustrated, as she revealed in that interview. She explained:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accio-quote.org/articles/2005/0705-tlc_mugglenet-anelli-2.htm |title=2005: Accio Quote!, the largest archive of J.K. Rowling interviews on the web |publisher=Accio-quote.org |date=16 July 2005 |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|Well, you see, I'm a relative newcomer to the world of shipping, because for a long time, I didn't go on the net and look up Harry Potter. A long time. Occasionally I had to, because there were weird news stories or something that I would have to go and check, because I was supposed to have said something I hadn\u2019t said. I had never gone and looked at fan sites, and then one day I did and oh&nbsp;\u2014 my&nbsp;\u2014 god. Five hours later or something, I get up from the computer shaking slightly [all laugh]. 'What is going on?\u2019 And it was during that first mammoth session that I met the shippers, and it was a most extraordinary thing. I had no idea there was this huge underworld seething beneath me.}}\n\nIn a later posting on MuggleNet, Spartz explained:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mugglenet.com/newsfusion/fullnews.php?id=972 |title=THE INTERVIEW! Part two |publisher=MuggleNet |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028134002/http://www.mugglenet.com/newsfusion/fullnews.php?id=972 |archive-date=28 October 2007 |url-status=dead |accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|My comments weren't directed at the shippers who acknowledged that Harry/Hermione was a long shot but loved the idea of them together. It was directed at the \"militant\" shippers who ''insisted'' that there was overwhelming canon proof and that everyone else was too blind to see it. You were delusional; you saw what you wanted to see and you have no one to blame for that but yourselves.}}\n\nRowling has continued to make references, less humorous and more, to the severity of the shipper conflicts. In one instance she has joked about trying to think of ways of proving to Emerson, when inviting him for the aforementioned interview, that it was really her and not \"some angry Harry/Hermione shipper trying to lure him down a dark alleyway\";<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/extrastuff_view.cfm?id=21 |title=Meeting Melissa and Emerson |website=[[J. K. Rowling]] |archive-date=16 March 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060316221055/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/extrastuff_view.cfm?id=21 |url-status=dead |accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref> In another, she has described her impression of the Harry Potter fandom's shipping debates as \"cyber gang warfare\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accio-quote.org/articles/2006/0801-radiocityreading1.html |title=2006: Accio Quote!, the largest archive of J.K. Rowling interviews on the web |publisher=Accio-quote.org |date=1 August 2006 |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nRowling stated in an interview in February 2014 in ''Wonderland'' Magazine that she thought that realistically Hermione and Ron had \"too much fundamental incompatibility.\" She stated that Hermione and Ron were written together \"as a form of wish fulfillment\" as way to reconcile a relationship she herself was once in. She went on to say that perhaps with marriage counseling Ron and Hermione would have been all right.<ref>West, Kelly. [https://www.cinemablend.com/pop/What-J-K-Rowling-Actually-Said-About-Hermione-Relationships-With-Ron-Harry-62153.html \"What J.K. Rowling Actually Said About Hermione's Relationships With Ron And Harry\"], Cinema Blend, 7 February 2014. Retrieved on 2 October 2014.</ref> She also went on to say in a talk at Exeter University that Harry's love for Ginny is true, thereby denying any potential canon relationship between Harry and Hermione.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://filthysquib.tumblr.com/post/76130596653/ive-just-got-back-from-the-jk-rowling-lecture |title = Tumblr}}</ref>\n\n===Other relationships===\nOn a less intense scale, other relationships have been doted upon in the fandom from suggestive hints or explicit statements throughout canon, such as those between Draco Malfoy and [[Pansy Parkinson]], [[Harry Potter's]] parents [[James Potter (character)|James Potter]] and [[Lily Evans]], [[Rubeus Hagrid]] and [[Olympe Maxime]], or [[Percy Weasley]] and [[Minor Ravenclaws#Penelope Clearwater|Penelope Clearwater]], or Rose Granger-Weasley and Scorpius Malfoy. A potential relationship between [[Neville Longbottom]] and [[Luna Lovegood]] was originally dispelled by Rowling,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/rumours_view.cfm?id=24 |title=Luna and Neville will hook up in HP&THBP |work=J. K. Rowling Official Site |last=Rowling |first=J. K. |accessdate=14 January 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070204111459/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/rumours_view.cfm?id=24 |archivedate=4 February 2007 }}</ref> though she later retracted this and said she noticed a slight attraction between them in ''Deathly Hallows''.<ref name=wild-about-harry>{{cite news|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/19959323/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070801083035/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/19959323/|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 August 2007|date=25 July 2007|accessdate=26 July 2007|publisher=[[MSNBC]]|last=Brown|first=Jen|title=Finished Potter? Rowling tells what happened next.}}</ref> \n\nSome couples, besides Harry and Ginny and Ron and Hermione, have been explicitly stated in the series: [[Bill Weasley]] and [[Fleur Delacour]] are married in ''Deathly Hallows'' after dating throughout ''Half-Blood Prince''.<ref>Rowling, J. K. (2007). ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows]]'' (in English). [[London]]: [[Bloomsbury Publishing|Bloomsbury]]/[[New York City]]: [[Scholastic Corporation|Scholastic]], et al. UK {{ISBN|0-7475-9105-9}}/US {{ISBN|0-545-01022-5}}, chapter 8.</ref> In ''Half-Blood Prince'', [[Nymphadora Tonks]] keeps her feelings for [[Remus Lupin]] to herself, but remains depressed when he refuses her advances; he feels that his being a werewolf would not create a safe relationship.<ref>Rowling, J. K. (2005). ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]'' (in English). [[London]]: [[Bloomsbury Publishing|Bloomsbury]]/[[New York City]]: [[Scholastic Corporation|Scholastic]], et al. UK {{ISBN|0-7475-8108-8}}/US {{ISBN|0-439-78454-9}}, chapter 29.</ref> Tonks professes her love for him at the end of the book, and she and Lupin have been married by the beginning of ''Deathly Hallows'' and have a son 'Teddy' later in the book.<ref>Rowling, ''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows'', chapter 1.</ref> Other couples, such as Harry and Draco or Lupin and [[Sirius Black]], are favorites among fans who read fan fiction about them. There is also debate about Lily and Severus vs. James.<ref name=potter-slash/><ref name=observer-lumos/>\n\n==Roleplaying games==\n[[Image:MuggleQuidditch.jpg|thumb|left|270px|[[Millikin University]] students at their biannual [[Muggle Quidditch]] tournament, a form of live action roleplay.]]\n[[Roleplaying]] is a central feature of the Harry Potter fandom. There are two primary forms: internet-based roleplay and live-action roleplay, or [[LARP]].\n\nLARPing often involves re-enacting or creating an original Quidditch team. Match rules and style of play vary among fandom events, but they are generally kept as close as possible to the sport envisioned by Rowling. The 2006 Lumos symposium included a Quidditch tournament played in water.<ref name=lumos-water-quidditch-rules>{{cite web|url=http://lumos2006.org/quidditch.shtml|title=Water Quidditch|publisher=Lumos 2006|accessdate=16 February 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070104124150/http://lumos2006.org/quidditch.shtml|archivedate=4 January 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> More common are ground-based games such as the handball style developed by USA Team Handball and featured at the [[MuggleNet]]-sponsored ''Spellbound'' event, as well as the [[Muggle Quidditch]] style played intramurally at [[Millikin University]] (at left).<ref>{{cite web|publisher=MuggleNet |url=http://www.mugglenet.com/spellbound.shtml |title=Spellbound! |accessdate=29 June 2006 |date=6 June 2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060906111731/http://www.mugglenet.com/spellbound.shtml |archivedate=6 September 2006 }}</ref> This version of quidditch has grown past intramural play, is far from LARPing, and has an international governing body, the IQA.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=IQA|url=http://www.internationalquidditch.org| title=The International Quidditch Association| accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nInternet-based roleplay tries to simulate the Hogwarts experience.  Most{{which|date=March 2013}} sites are forum-based, emphasizing taking classes taught by staff members in order for the players to earn points for their respective houses. Some{{which|date=March 2013}} internet-based roleplay sites go more in depth into canon and storylines, and do not specifically rely on posting as the only method for gaining house points while others{{which|date=March 2013}} have expanded to include activities such as Quidditch, dueling, and board-wide plots. Hogwarts-school.net (est. 2000), for example, is a forum-based roleplaying game which allows players to take classes, engage in extracurriculars, and also has many options for adult characters in St. Mungos, the Daily Prophet, and the Ministry of Magic.\n\n2007 saw the launch of World of Hogwarts,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldofhogwarts.org/intro.htm |title=Introduction |publisher=The World of Hogwarts |accessdate=16 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120623195942/http://www.worldofhogwarts.org/intro.htm |archivedate=23 June 2012 }}</ref> a completely free [[MMORPG]] [[Harry Potter]] roleplaying game in [[Second Life]], set ten years after the Battle of [[Hogwarts]]. Here, roleplayers can create an avatar and interact with other students, attend lessons organized by other roleplayers, play [[Quidditch]], sit for their exams, earn and lose points for their house, visit [[Hogsmeade]], [[Diagon Alley]] and the Forbidden Forest, get a job at the [[Ministry of Magic]], explore several secret passages within the castle, and even immerse themselves into intricate and well-composed storyline plots that have, through time, grown into the canon rules of the game.\n\nA website created by ISO Interactive, called the Chamber of Chat is a free online interactive virtual world under a [[Massively multiplayer online game|MMO]] format. Although not a full [[MMORPG]] format, Chamber of Chat is set up with 3D virtual chatrooms and avatars where fans can socially interact with each other in [[Pictionary]] and Harry Potter [[Trivia]]l games or participate in discussion groups about Harry Potter or Film media or perform plays as a theater group to other fans as audience. They hold special community event such as Harry Potters Birthday or Halloween and have seasonal house competitions.  Fans are able to create their own avatars, collect or be rewarded coins to purchase furniture items for their own \"clubhouse\". However, the website emphasizes more social interaction between fans' avatars to stimulate the Hogwarts student experience. \"Chamber of Chat is a graphical Social Virtual World with a few [[Facebook]] plug-ins. The Harry Potter Virtual World is designed for fans. This give users the feeling that they are interacting in the actual 3D world. You can hang out with other students, relax in the common room, mingle at the pub, play games like Pictionary and even download cool looking wallpapers.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chamberofchat.com/ |title=Chamber of Chat Harry Potter Interactive 3D World |publisher=Chamberofchat.com |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref> On 19 April 2007, Chamber of Chat was awarded [[Adobe Systems|Adobe]] Site of the day. Chamber of chat has also been awarded a place among the SmartFoxServer Showcase. \"Chamber of Chat is an MMO community inspired to the magic worlds of the Harry Potter saga. The application is a great example of integration between Director/Shockwave (client) and SmartFoxServer PRO.\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smartfoxserver.com/showcase/ |title=massive multiplayer game server for Flash, Unity 3D, iPhone/iPad and Android games, MMO, virtual worlds and communities |publisher=SmartFoxServer |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref> Chamber of Chat has been a long time associated branch of The Leaky network and although as part of the network with [[The Leaky Cauldron (website)|The Leaky Cauldron]], [[Pottercast]] and \"Ask [[Peeves]]\" search engine, it was ranked number two behind [[Indiana Jones|Indiana Jones's]] TheRaider.Net out of 25 essential fansites of \"The Best of the Web\" by [[Entertainment Weekly]] in December 2007.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20167049_24,00.html | work=Entertainment Weekly | title=25 Essential Fansites}}</ref>\n\nOther sites use modified versions of [[phpBB]] that allow for a certain level of [[interactive]] roleplaying and are what is commonly referred to as \"[[Play-by-post role-playing game|forum-based roleplaying]]\". Interactive gaming can include [[player versus player]] features, a form of currency for making purchases in stores, and [[non-player characters]] such as monsters that must be fought to gain levels and experience points. However, these features are more prevalent in games that are not forum-based. Advancement in such games is usually dependent on live chat, multiplayer cooperation, and fighting as opposed to taking classes or simply posting to earn points for one's \"house\"; like at Hogwarts, players in forum-based games are sometimes sorted into a different group distinguishing different values within a person.\n\nRoleplaying also occurs in [[Improv comedy|long-form improvisational]] theater. Several American and British improv troupes are devoted to the Potter genre. These include Melbourne's ''[https://www.improvisedpotter.com.au/ Completely Improvised Potter] London's [[Potted Potter]]'' and Los Angeles's ''[http://harrypotterimprov.com/ The Show That Shall Not Be Named].''\n\n==Iconic landmarks tours==\n[[Image:Glenfinnan Viaduct, Scotland.jpg|200px|right|thumb|The [[Glenfinnan viaduct]], which the [[Hogwarts Express]] passes over when it travels to Hogwarts in the films.]]\nSome travel agencies have organised a subdivision to create tours specifically highlighting iconic landmarks in the world of ''Harry Potter''. HP Fan Trips, offered by Beyond Boundaries Travel since 2004 in conjunction with fan site [[HPANA]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hpfantrips.com/about/|title=About HP Fan Trips|publisher=HP Fan Trips|accessdate=21 April 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070506200724/http://hpfantrips.com/about/|archive-date=6 May 2007|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=wp-hp-tours>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/12/29/AR2006122900440.html|title=On Holiday With Harry Potter|work=The Washington Post|date=31 December 2006|accessdate=21 April 2007|last=Sachs|first=Andrea}}</ref> was designed by and for fans of the series, and tours noteworthy ''Potter''-related locations in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news|title=Firm conjures up a host of Harry Potter-theme tours|work=Daily Herald (Arlington Heights, IL)|last=Hobica|first=George|author2=Kim Liang Tan|date=18 March 2007|page=2}}</ref> Since 2004, they have exclusively chartered steam locomotive [[GWR 4900 Class 5972 Olton Hall|#5972 Olton Hall]], the locomotive used in the films as the [[Hogwarts Express]], as well as the carriages labeled as such and seen in the movies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hpfantrips.com/2007/oltonhall/oltonhall.cfm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070302091514/http://www.hpfantrips.com/2007/oltonhall/oltonhall.cfm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2 March 2007 |title=HP Fan Trips 2007 Exclusive Train Ride |publisher=HP Fan Trips |accessdate=21 April 2007 }}</ref> The travel agency Your Man in Europe began hosting Magical Tours in 2006, in conjunction with fan site [[MuggleNet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://magicaltours.org/contest-rules.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070328193710/http://magicaltours.org/contest-rules.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=28 March 2007 |title=2007 MuggleNet, Magical Tours, and Alivan's CONTEST RULES |publisher=Magical Tours |accessdate=15 April 2007 }}</ref> They offer four different tours through England and Scotland.\n\n[[Image:Alnwick Castle - Northumberland - 140804.jpg|250px|left|thumb|[[Alnwick Castle]], the castle used for filming exterior shots of [[Hogwarts]] in the [[Harry Potter (film series)|''Potter'' films]].]]\nThese tours primarily feature locations used for shooting in the [[Harry Potter (film)|films]], though some trips include a Chinese restaurant in Edinburgh, which was once Nicholson's Cafe, where Rowling wrote much of the manuscript for ''[[Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone]]'', and [[Edinburgh Castle]], where Rowling read from the sixth book on the night of its release to an audience of children.<ref name=wp-hp-tours/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/features/20050715-1930-potter-castle.html|title=Lucky fans hear J.K. Rowling read at Edinburgh castle|date=15 July 2005|accessdate=21 April 2007|last=McAloon|first=Catherine|work=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080624230415/http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/features/20050715-1930-potter-castle.html|archivedate=24 June 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Filming locations visited include [[Alnwick Castle]], where some exterior locations of [[Hogwarts]] are shot, places in [[Fort William, Highland|Fort William]], Scotland; [[Glen Nevis]], Scotland; the [[Glenfinnan viaduct]]; [[Christ Church Cathedral, Oxford|Christ Church Cathedral]] in [[Oxford]] and the Cloisters located within [[New College, Oxford]].<ref name=wp-hp-tours/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/oxford/harry_potter/oxford_tour.shtml|title=Harry Potter video|work=BBC|accessdate=21 April 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Wizard rock==\n{{Main|Wizard rock}}\n[[Image:Harry and the Potters HM.JPG|right|thumb|250px|[[Harry and the Potters]] perform at the [[Horace Mann School]] in [[Riverdale, Bronx]], [[New York (state)|New York]].]]\n'''Wizard music''' (sometimes shorthanded as '''Wrock''') is a musical movement dating from 2000 in [[Massachusetts]] with Harry and the Potters, though it has grown internationally<ref name=poststan>{{cite news|url=http://www.syracuse.com/articles/cny/index.ssf?/base/living-3/118492494174900.xml&coll=1|title=Wizard Rock|publisher=[[The Post-Standard]]|date=20 July 2007|accessdate=31 July 2007|last=Loftus|first=Meghan|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071007095010/http://www.syracuse.com/articles/cny/index.ssf?%2Fbase%2Fliving-3%2F118492494174900.xml&coll=1|archivedate=7 October 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=279730 |title=The unexpected wizards of rock and roll |date=20 July 2007 |accessdate=31 July 2007 |publisher=[[MSN]] |last=Davies |first=Shaun |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120525193856/news.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=279730 |archivedate=25 May 2012 }}</ref> and has expanded to at least 750 bands.<ref>[http://wizrocklopedia.com/index.php/band-listings/ Wizrocklopedia band listings] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820100938/http://wizrocklopedia.com/index.php/band-listings |date=20 August 2008 }}</ref> Wrock bands mostly consist of young musicians that write and perform songs about the ''Harry Potter'' universe,<ref name=yule-ball-philly>{{cite news|url=http://articles.philly.com/2006-11-28/entertainment/25406043_1_whomping-willows-potter-phenomenon-fifth-book|title=Yule Ball rolls into Philly Show spotlights Harry Potter-themed rock|last=Brady|first=Shaun|publisher=[[Philadelphia Daily News]]|date=28 November 2006|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Business/FunMoney/Story?id=3371717&page=1|title=Harry Potter 'Wrockers' Conjure Musical Magic|date=13 July 2007|accessdate=31 July 2007|publisher=[[ABC News]]|last=Humphries|first=Rachel}}</ref> and these songs are often written from the point of view of a particular character in the books, usually the character who features in the band's name. If they are performing live, they may also [[cosplay]], or dress as, that character.<ref name=handp-boston-globe>{{cite news|url=https://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2004/09/16/sibling_musicians_bring_out_the_punk_in_harry_potter/|last=Sweeney|first=Emily|title=Sibling musicians bring out the 'punk' in Harry Potter|date=16 September 2004|accessdate=26 January 2007|publisher=The Boston Globe}}</ref>\n\nIn contrast to mainstream bands that have some songs incorporating literary references among a wider repertoire of music (notably [[Led Zeppelin]] to ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]''),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fortwayne.com/mld/newssentinel/living/16381778.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070330064614/http://www.fortwayne.com/mld/newssentinel/living/16381778.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=30 March 2007 |title=Four reasons you should raid your parents' music collection |date=4 January 2007 |accessdate=26 January 2007 |publisher=Fort Wayne News Sentinel |last=Gleason |first=Janelle }}</ref> wizard rock bands take their inspiration entirely from the ''Harry Potter'' universe.<ref name=handp-boston-globe/> In preserving the promotion of reading, too, bands like to perform in libraries, bookstores, and schools.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eskimolabs.com/hp/band.htm |title=Harry and the Potters: The Band |publisher=[[Harry and the Potters]] |accessdate=27 February 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070227215243/http://www.eskimolabs.com/hp/band.htm |archivedate=27 February 2007 }}</ref> The bands have also performed at the fan conventions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/books/feature/2007/06/01/phoenix_rising/|title=Potterpalooza|date=1 June 2007|accessdate=9 August 2007|last=Traister|first=Rebecca|publisher=Salon.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509155513/http://www.salon.com/books/feature/2007/06/01/phoenix_rising/|archivedate=9 May 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Documentaries==\n\n===''We Are Wizards''===\n'''''We Are Wizards''''' is a feature-length documentary by [[Josh Koury]] about the ''Harry Potter'' fandom. It features Wizard rock bands [[Harry and the Potters]], [[Draco and the Malfoys]], The Hungarian Horntails, and The Whomping Willows. The film also features [[Heather Lawver]], [[Melissa Anelli]], and [[Brad Neely]].<ref>[http://www.wearewizards-themovie.com/ We Are Wizards - The Movie] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080325134913/http://www.wearewizards-themovie.com/ |date=25 March 2008 }}</ref> ''We Are Wizards'' had its World Premiere at the SXSW film festival in 2008, then traveled to 20 film festivals worldwide.  The film opened theatrically in 5 cities on 14 November 2008.  The film can be seen on Hulu.com, and DVD.\n\n===''The Fandom Fan Diaries: Wizard's Gone W!ld''===\n'''''The Fandom Fan Diaries: Wizard's Gone W!ld''''' is a documentary web series that is based on fandom submissions. The producers Miranda Marshall and Amy Henderson starting accepting video submissions in early March 2009 and plan to accept them through 2013. ''WiZarDs Gone W!LD'' is affiliated with ''The Fan Book of HP Fans'', yet another fandom project based on submissions that has recently extended its submission deadline date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.facebook.com/home.php?#/group.php?gid=53471403919&ref=ts |title=The Fan Book of HP Fans *A Fan Project* |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref><ref>http://www.wizardsgonewild.webs.com {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111016135818/http://wizardsgonewild.webs.com/ |date=16 October 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===''The Wizard Rockumentary''===\n'''''The Wizard Rockumentary: A Movie about Rocking and Rowling''''' is a feature documentary chronicling the rise of Harry Potter tribute bands. Producers Megan and Mallory Schuyler travelled around the United States compiling interviews and concert footage of bands including [[Harry and the Potters]], [[Draco and the Malfoys]], The Remus Lupins, The Whomping Willow, The Moaning Myrtles, Roonil Wazlib, Snidget, and The Hermione Crookshanks Experience. The film was released in April 2008 and has screened in libraries around the country. The producers are currently negotiating broadcast and home video rights.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wizardrockumentary.com/about.html |title=About Us |publisher=Wizardrockumentary.com |accessdate=16 June 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206033559/http://www.wizardrockumentary.com/about.html |archive-date=6 February 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===''Proyecto Patronus''===\n'''''Project Patronus: magic of a generation''''' (''Proyecto Patronus: la magia de una generaci\u00f3n'') is a Spanish documentary based on the Harry Potter saga. It covers the franchise's influence on a generation of young people, and deals with the multiple [[values]], such as friendship, love, courage and respect, which are reflected in the books. Numerous professionals in [[psychology]] and [[pedagogy]] who have studied the significance of the saga appear. The film was released in 2016 and has screened in film festivals around Spain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elmundo.es/enredados/2015/09/07/55ed602722601de96a8b457a.html |title=Proyecto Patronus |publisher=Elmundo.com |accessdate=7 September 2015|date=7 September 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Health==\nIn 2003, Dr. Howard J. Bennett coined the term \"Hogwarts headache\" in a letter to the [[New England Journal of Medicine]] shortly after the release of the longest book in the series, ''[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix|Order of the Phoenix]]''.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.medicinenet.com/script/main/art.asp?articlekey=25035 |title = Definition of Hogwarts headache}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/uk/newsid_2661000/2661257.stm|title=Potter book five: on sale on 21 June|date=15 January 2003|accessdate=16 April 2007|work=BBC Newsround}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/books/news/2005-07-13-potter-rumors_x.htm|title=Rumors run wild about 'Harry'|date=13 July 2005|accessdate=16 April 2007|work=[[USA Today]]|last=Memmott|first=Carol}}</ref> He described it as a mild condition, a [[tension headache]] possibly accompanied by neck or wrist pains, caused by unhealthily long reading sessions of ''Harry Potter''. The symptoms resolved themselves within days of finishing the book. His prescription of taking reading breaks was rejected by two of the patients on which he discovered this headache.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Hogwarts Headaches&nbsp;\u2014 Misery for Muggles|first=Howard J.|last=Bennett|date=30 October 2003|journal=[[New England Journal of Medicine]]|volume=349|issue=18|pmid=14585953|doi=10.1056/NEJM200310303491821|page=1779}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1056/NEJM200310303491821| pmid=14585953| title=Hogwarts Headaches \u2014 Misery for Muggles| journal=New England Journal of Medicine| volume=349| issue=18| pages=1779| year=2003| last1=Bennett| first1=Howard J.}}</ref>\n\nResearchers at [[John Radcliffe Hospital]] in [[Oxford]] found in 2005 that the admission rate of children with traumatic injuries to the city's [[emergency department|ER]]s plummeted on the publication weekends of both ''[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix|Order of the Phoenix]]'' and ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince|Half-Blood Prince]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/03/health/03safe.html?ex=1185508800&en=1b1e26eb8831fcc9&ei=5070 |title=Safety: With Harry Potter, Injuries Dip Like Magic |first=Eric |last=Nagourney |work=[[New York Times]] |accessdate=25 July 2007 | date=3 January 2006}}</ref> This was due to the volume of children reading Harry Potter rather than engaging in riskier outdoor activities, such as riding of bicycles and scooters, climbing trees or playing sports. The study was led by Dr. Stephen Gwilym whose paper \"hypothesized that there is a place for a committee of safety-conscious, talented writers who could produce high quality books for the purpose of injury prevention,\" noting a potential problem with this strategy: \"Obviously, if children are always in reading books and not outside getting exercise, there is a long-term risk of obesity, rickets and lack of sunlight.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://consumer.healthday.com/general-health-information-16/emergencies-and-first-aid-news-227/harry-potter-books-keep-kids-safe-529859.html | title=Harry Potter Books Keep Kids Safe}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Harry Potter fandom}}\n{{Wikipedia books|Harry Potter}}\n{{Portal|Children and Young Adult Literature}}\n*[[Bartimaeus Sequence]]\n*[[Muggle]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\nWaters, G. Mithrandir, A. (2003). [http://www.goodreads.com/author/show/9830.Galadriel_Waters ''Ultimate Unofficial Guide to the Mysteries of Harry Potter (analysis of Books 1-4)'']. Niles, IL: Wizarding World Press.\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite journal |last1=Karlsson |first1=Marie |last2=Olin-Scheller |first2=Christina |title=\"Let\u00b4s Party!\" Harry Potter fan fiction sites as social settings for narrative gender constructions |journal=[[Gender and Language]] |volume=9 |issue=2 |pages=167&ndash;188 |doi=10.1558/genl.v9i2.17330 |year=2015 |ref=harv }}\n\n{{Fandom}}\n{{Fan fiction}}\n{{Harry Potter}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harry Potter Fandom}}\n[[Category:Harry Potter fandom|Fandom]]\n[[Category:Literary fandom]]\n[[Category:Film and video fandom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Harry Potter'' fandom}}\n[[File:Long Beach Comic & Horror Con 2011 - Hogwarts students (6301701262).jpg|thumb|Fans dressed as Hogwarts students at Long Beach Comic & Horror Con 2011]]\n{{Fantasy|state=collapsed}}\n'''''Harry Potter'' fandom''' refers to the [[fandom|community of fans]] of the ''[[Harry Potter]]'' books and movies who participate in entertainment activities that revolve around the series, such as reading and writing [[fan fiction]], creating and soliciting [[fan art]], engaging in [[role-playing game]]s, socializing on ''Harry Potter''-based [[Internet forum|forums]], and more. The fandom interacts online as well as offline through activities such as [[fan convention]]s, participating in cosplay, tours of iconic landmarks relevant to the [[Harry Potter|books]] and production of the [[Harry Potter (film series)|films]], and parties held for the midnight release of each book and film.\n\nBy the fourth ''Harry Potter'' book, the legions of fans had grown so large that considerable security measures were taken to ensure that no book was purchased before the official release date.<ref name=cnn-hbp>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2005/SHOWBIZ/books/07/14/harry.potter/index.html|title=Harry Potter hits midnight frenzy|date=15 July 2005|work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=15 January 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061221021913/http://www.cnn.com/2005/SHOWBIZ/books/07/14/harry.potter/index.html |archivedate = 21 December 2006}}</ref> ''Harry Potter'' is considered one of the few [[Four-quadrant movie|four-quadrant]], multi-generation spanning franchises that exist today, despite Rowling's original marketing of the books to [[tween]]s and [[teen]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/07/20/AR2005072000038.html|title=The Magic Of 'Potter' Not Just For Kids|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=21 July 2005|first=Philip|last=Rucker|accessdate=28 February 2007}}</ref><ref name=ew-gof-midnight>{{cite news|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,276735_2,00.html|title=Wild About Harry|date=31 August 2005|accessdate=4 March 2007|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last=Fierman|first=Daniel|quote=When I buy the books for my grandchildren, I have them all gift wrapped but one...that's for me. And I haven't been 12 for over 50 years.}}</ref>\n\n==Pottermania==\n[[Image:Harry Potter lines.jpg|300px|left|thumb|''Potter'' fans wait in lines outside a [[Borders Group|Borders]] bookstore for their copy of ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]''.]]\n[[File:Harry Potter fans imitates Harry, Lumos Maxima.jpg|thumb|A fan imitates Harry casting the ''[[Magic in Harry Potter|Lumos]]'' spell]]\nPottermania is an informal term first used around 1999 describing the craze ''[[Harry Potter]]'' fans have had over the series.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.accio-quote.org/articles/1999/1099-chictimes-tucker.html|title=No end in sight for Pottermania|date=22 October 1999|accessdate=14 April 2007|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|format=reprint|last=Tucker|first=Ernest}}</ref> Fans held midnight parties to celebrate the release of the final four books at bookstores which stayed open on the night leading into the date of the release.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4191/is_20050716/ai_n14779049 |title=Midnight magic for Potter fans |date=16 July 2005 |accessdate=15 January 2007 |work=The Colorado Springs Gazette |last=Simmons |first=Matthew |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071210012715/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4191/is_20050716/ai_n14779049 |archivedate=10 December 2007 }}</ref> In 2005, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' listed the midnight release of ''[[Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire]]'' as one of \"Entertainment's Top Moments\" of the previous 25 years.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1100001,00.html|title=Entertainment's Top Moments|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=31 August 2005|accessdate=14 March 2007}}</ref>\n\nDiehard fans of the series are called \"'''Potterheads'''\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Like Magic, Muggles Make New Harry Potter Play Disappear from Bookstores |author=Ashley Ross |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/01/nyregion/harry-potter-and-the-cursed-child-disappears-from-stores.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=31 July 2016 |accessdate=13 December 2016}}</ref> Some even theme their [[weddings]] around Harry Potter. A Bridal Guide featured two real weddings soon before the release of the final movie, which quickly spread through the fandom via [[Facebook]], [[Twitter]], and [[Tumblr]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bridalguide.com/blogs/bridal-buzz/harry-potter-theme-weddings |title=Wedding Magic: Amazing Harry Potter-Themed Weddings |work=[[Bridal Guide]] |accessdate=13 July 2011 | date=29 July 2011}}</ref>\n \nThe craze over the series was referenced in [[Lauren Weisberger]]'s 2003 novel ''[[The Devil Wears Prada (novel)|The Devil Wears Prada]]'' as well as its [[The Devil Wears Prada (film)|2006 film adaptation]]. In the story, the protagonist Andrea Sachs is ordered to retrieve two copies of the next installment in the series for her boss's twins before they are published so that they can be privately flown to France, where the twins and their mother are on holiday.<ref>{{cite book|last=Weisberger|first=Lauren|authorlink=Lauren Weisberger|title=The Devil Wears Prada|year=2003|publisher=Broadway Books|location=New York City|isbn=978-0-7679-1476-5|page=[https://archive.org/details/devilwearspra00weis/page/79 79]|title-link=The Devil Wears Prada (novel)}}</ref>\n\nSome celebrities who are fans of ''Harry Potter'' include [[Lily Allen]],<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/harry-potter-20th-anniversary-jk-rowling-wizarding-world-709478/ | title='Harry Potter' at 20: Artists Reveal Tattoos, Tears, Tour Stories Inspired by the Wizarding World| date=September 2018}}</ref> [[Guillermo del Toro]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://collider.com/guillermo-del-toro-haunted-mansion-harry-potter-interview/ |title=Guillermo del Toro Talks HAUNTED MANSION and His Love of HARRY POTTER |date=7 August 2012 |first=Steve |last=Weintraub |website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref> [[Stephen King]],<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2007/07/06/harry-fans-break-out-tissues |title=Harry fans, break out the tissues! |first=Stephen |last=King |journal=Entertainment Weekly |date=6 July 2007 |accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref> [[Keira Knightley]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1595489/harry-potter-gets-love-from-robert-pattinson-lupe-fiasco-keira-knightley-and-more-celeb-fans/ |title='Harry Potter' Gets Love From Robert Pattinson, Lupe Fiasco, Keira Knightley And More Celeb Fans |date=23 September 2008 |first=Jennifer |last=Vineyard |website=MTV |accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref> [[Jennifer Lawrence]],<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.hypable.com/jennifer-lawrence-harry-potter-fan/ |title = 'The Hunger Games' Jennifer Lawrence loves 'Harry Potter'|date = 19 November 2012}}</ref> [[Evanna Lynch]], [[Liam Neeson]],<ref>http://www.contactmusic.com/pics/ld/ny_premiere_harry_potter_4_161110/liam_neeson_3100325.jpg</ref> [[Barack Obama]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1557929/Barack-Obama-under-the-Harry-Potter-spell.html |title=Barack Obama under the Harry Potter spell |date=19 July 2007 |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |first=Julian |last=Kossoff |accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref> [[Simon Pegg]],<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QgBFsI10sEA</ref> [[Seth Rogen]],<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.cinemablend.com/new/Harry-Potter-Killing-Famous-People-Seth-Rogen-Evan-Goldberg-Talk-End-36738.html?story_page=3 | title=Harry Potter and Killing Famous People: Seth Rogen and Evan Goldberg Talk This is the End| date=3 April 2013}}</ref> and [[Matt Smith (actor)|Matt Smith]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/fantastic-beasts/news/a637944/is-matt-smith-a-good-choice-for-harry-potter-spin-off-fantastic-beasts/ |title = Who would you cast in Fantastic Beasts?|date = 25 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Fan sites==\nThere are many fan web sites about ''Harry Potter'' on the Internet, the oldest ones dating to about 1997 or 1998.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.zdnet.com/2100-9595_22-503255.html|date=20 December 2000|accessdate=2 January 2007|publisher=Wall Street Journal|format=reprint|title=Warner Bros. claims Harry Potter sites|last=Grunier|first=Stephanie|author2=John Lippman |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061116075618/http://news.zdnet.com/2100-9595_22-503255.html |archivedate = 16 November 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/general/googleeyed-over-harry/2005/07/15/1121429358851.html?oneclick=true|publisher=[[The Age]]|title=Google-eyed over Harry|date=16 July 2005|first=Jo|last=Chandler|accessdate=28 February 2007 | location=Melbourne}}</ref><ref name=the-star-sites>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/artsentertainment/article/201974|title=Potter sites wild about Harry|date=11 April 2007|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]|accessdate=13 April 2007|last=Italie|first=Hillel}}</ref> [[J. K. Rowling]] has an open relationship with her fan base, and since 2004 periodically hands out a \"fan site award\" on her official web site.<ref name=fansites-main>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite.cfm|last=Rowling|first=J. K.|title=Section: Fan Sites|work=J. K. Rowling Official Site|accessdate=2 January 2007|authorlink=J. K. Rowling|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061230195904/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite.cfm|archivedate=30 December 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The first site to receive the award was Immeritus, a fan site mostly devoted to [[Sirius Black]], and about which Rowling wrote, \"I am so proud of the fact that a character, whom I always liked very much, though he never appeared as much more than a brooding presence in the books, has gained a passionate fan-club.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=1|last=Rowling|first=J. K.|title=Section: Fan Sites: Immeritus|work=J. K. Rowling Official Site|accessdate=2 January 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110623034807/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=1|archivedate=23 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, after Immeritus, Rowling bestowed the honour upon four sites. The first was Godric's Hollow;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hp-lexicon.org/about/sources/jkr.com/jkr-com-timeline.html|title=J. K. Rowling Official Site: Timeline|work=[[The Harry Potter Lexicon]]|accessdate=2 January 2006}}</ref> for some time however, the site's domain name was occupied by advertisers and its content was lost<ref>{{cite web|url=http://godricshollow.org/|title=Godricshollow.org|accessdate=9 January 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060104212857/http://www.godricshollow.org/|archivedate=4 January 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and there is no further record on Rowling's site that Godric's Hollow ever received the award,<ref name=fansites-main/> although in 2010 the website came back online again albeit with a lot of content missing. The next site was the [[Harry Potter Lexicon]], an online encyclopedia Rowling has admitted to visiting while writing away from home rather than buying a copy of her books in a store. She called it \"for the dangerously obsessive; my natural home.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=14|last=Rowling|first=J. K.|accessdate=2 January 2006|work=J. K. Rowling Official Site|title=Section: Fan Sites: The Harry Potter Lexicon|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060316220934/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=14|archivedate=16 March 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The third site of 2004 was [[MuggleNet]], a web site featuring the latest news in the Potter world, among editorials, forums, and a podcast. Rowling wrote when giving the award, \"It's high time I paid homage to the mighty MuggleNet,\" and listed all the features she loved, including \"the pretty-much-exhaustive information on all books and films.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=15|last=Rowling|first=J. K.|title=Section: Fan Sites: MuggleNet|work=J. K. Rowling Official Site|accessdate=2 January 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061206023706/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=15|archivedate=6 December 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The last site was [[HPANA]], the first fan site Rowling ever visited, \"faster off the mark with Harry Potter news than any other site\" Rowling knows, and \"fantastically user-friendly.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=16 |last=Rowling |first=J. K. |title=Section: Fan Sites: HPANA |work=J. K. Rowling Official Site |accessdate=2 January 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060216183428/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=16 |archivedate=16 February 2006 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, only [[The Leaky Cauldron (website)|The Leaky Cauldron]] was honored. In Rowling's words, \"it is about the worst kept secret on this website that I am a huge fan of The Leaky Cauldron,\" which she calls a \"wonderfully well designed mine of accurate information on all things Harry Potter.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=17|last=Rowling|first=J. K.|title=Section: Fan Sites: The Leaky Cauldron|work=J. K. Rowling Official Site|accessdate=2 January 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061209064200/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=17|archivedate=9 December 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On another occasion, Rowling has called the Leaky Cauldron her \"favourite fan site.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/static_downloads/jkr-ootp-rah.mp3 |title=JKR at Royal Albert Hall |date=26 June 2003 |publisher=The Leaky Cauldron |last=Rowling |first=J. K. |accessdate=9 January 2007 |format=QuickTime |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070704083555/http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/static_downloads/jkr-ootp-rah.mp3 |archivedate=4 July 2007 }}</ref> In 2006, the Brazilian website Potterish was the only site honoured, in recognition of its \"style, [its] Potter-expertise and [its] responsible reporting.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=18|last=Rowling|first=J. K.|title=Section: Fan Sites: Potterish.com|work=J. K. Rowling Official Site|accessdate=2 January 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070118084800/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=18|archivedate=18 January 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2007, [[Harry Potter Fan Zone]] received the award. Rowling recognized the insightful editorials as well as praised the site for its young and dedicated staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=19|last=Rowling|first=J. K.|title=Section: Fan Sites: Harry Potter Fan Zone.com|work=J. K. Rowling Official Site|accessdate=10 May 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070514034127/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=19|archivedate=14 May 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In December 2007, the award went to The Harry Potter Alliance, a campaign that seeks to end discrimination, genocide, poverty, AIDS, global warming, and other \"real-world Dark Arts\", relating these problems to the books. Rowling called the project \"extraordinary\" and \"most inspirational\", and paralleled its mission to \"the values for which Dumbledore's Army fought in the books\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=20|last=Rowling|first=J. K.|title=Section: Fan Sites: The HP Alliance|work=J. K. Rowling Official Site|accessdate=2 January 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080101171647/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/fansite_view.cfm?id=20|archivedate=1 January 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In an article about her in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', Rowling expressed her gratefulness at the site's successful work raising awareness and sign-up levels among anti-genocide coalitions.<ref name=jkr-time-dec-2007>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/personoftheyear/article/0,28804,1690753_1695388_1695436,00.html|title=J.K. Rowling|last=Gibbs|first=Nancy|publisher=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=2 January 2008|date=31 December 2007}}</ref>\n\nAt one time, [[Warner Bros.]], which owns the rights to ''Harry Potter'' and its affiliates, tried to shut down the sites. The unsuccessful attempt eventually led to their inviting the webmasters of the top sites to premieres of the films and tours of the film sets, because of their close connection with the fans. Warner Bros. executives have acknowledged that many fans are disappointed that certain elements of the books are left out, but not trying to avoid criticism, \"bringing the fan sites into the process is what we feel is really important.\"<ref name=the-star-sites/>\n\nThese fan sites contain news updates into the world of the [[Harry Potter|books]], [[Harry Potter (film)|films]], and [[List of Harry Potter films cast members|film cast members]] through the use of forums, image galleries, or video galleries.<ref>{{cite web|last=Anelli|first=Melissa|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/#static:sitefaq|title=A Brief (Believe it or Not) History of the Leaky Cauldron|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron|accessdate=3 January 2007}}</ref> They also host user-submitted creations, such as [[fan art]] or fan fiction.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/index.php?articleID=9355|title=Fan Art Contest&nbsp;\u2014 Design a \"Deathly Hallows\" Book Cover|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron|date=23 December 2006|accessdate=3 January 2007|last=Tynion|first=Julie}}</ref>\n\n===Podcasts===\n<!--A [[podcast]] is a media file that is distributed by unpaid subscription over the [[Internet]] using [[Web syndication|syndication]] [[Web feed|feeds]], for playback on mobile devices and [[personal computer]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://technology.guardian.co.uk/weekly/story/0,16376,1683937,00.html|title=Short shrift|date=2006-01-12|accessdate=2007-01-21|publisher=The Guardian|last=Arthur|first=Charles and Jack Schofield | location=London}}</ref>-->\nThe Harry Potter fandom has embraced [[podcast]]s as a regular, often weekly, insight to the latest discussion in the fandom. [[Apple Inc.]] has featured two of the podcasts, [[MuggleCast]] and [[PotterCast]].<ref name=apple-enews>{{cite news|url=https://www.apple.com/enews/2005/09/08enews1.html |title=Book corner: Secrets of Podcasting |date=8 September 2005 |accessdate=31 January 2007 |publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051227152737/http://www.apple.com/enews/2005/09/08enews1.html |archivedate=27 December 2005 |df=dmy }}</ref> Both have reached the top spot of [[iTunes]] podcast rankings and have been polled one of the top 50 favorite podcasts.<ref name=pr-newswire-mc>{{cite news|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/cgi-bin/stories.pl?ACCT=104&STORY=/www/story/11-08-2005/0004210790&EDATE=|title=Mugglenet.com Taps Limelight's Magic for Podcast Delivery of Harry Potter Content|date=8 November 2005|accessdate=31 January 2007|publisher=PR Newswire}}</ref> At the 2006 Podcast Awards, when MuggleCast and PotterCast each received two nominations for the same two categories, the two podcasts teamed up and requested listeners vote for PotterCast in the Best Entertainment category and MuggleCast in the People's Choice category. Both podcasts won these respective categories.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/index.php?articleID=8970|title=PotterCast Voted Best Entertainment Podcast at Podcast Awards|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron|date=15 August 2006|accessdate=27 February 2007|last=Anelli|first=Melissa}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://mugglenet.com/app/news/full_story/370 |title=MuggleCast wins People's Choice Award |date=2 October 2006 |accessdate=27 February 2007 |publisher=MuggleNet |last=Sims |first=Andrew |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061203022310/http://mugglenet.com/app/news/full_story/370 |archivedate=3 December 2006 }}</ref>\n\nMuggleCast, hosted by [[MuggleNet]] staffers, was created in August 2005, not long after the release of ''Half-Blood Prince''.<ref name=mugglecast-about>{{cite web|url=http://www.mugglenet.com/mugglecast/index.php?page=about.php|title=MuggleCast: About|accessdate=31 January 2007|publisher=MuggleCast}}</ref> Topics of the first show focused on [[Horcrux]]es, \"[[Death Eater#Regulus Black|R.A.B.]]\", the [[Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire (film)|''Goblet of Fire'' film]], which was due for release two months later, and the website DumbledoreIsNotDead.com.<ref name=mc-episode1-transcript>{{cite news|url=http://www.mugglenet.com/mugglecast/index.php?page=transcripts/1.php|date=7 August 2005|accessdate=31 January 2007|publisher=MuggleCast|title=MuggleCast EP1 Transcript}}</ref> Since then, MuggleCast has held chapter-by-chapter discussions, character analyses, and a discussion on a \"theory of the week\". MuggleCast has also added humour to their podcast with segments like \"Spy on Spartz,\" where the hosts would call MuggleNet webmaster Emerson Spartz and reveal his current location or activity with the listening audience. British staff member Jamie Lawrence tells a British joke of the week, and host Andrew Sims reads an email sent to MuggleNet with a strange request or incoherent talk (dubbed \"Huh?! Email of the Week\").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mugglenet.com/mugglecast/index.php?page=episodes_page1.php|title=MuggleCast Episodes 1 - 10|publisher=MuggleCast|accessdate=27 February 2007}}</ref> MuggleCast is currently the highest rated Harry Potter Podcast on the Internet. The MuggleCast website will continue to serve as a resource for other Harry Potter fans who want to rediscover the show.\n\nPotterCast was released less than two weeks after MuggleCast's first episode. Produced by [[The Leaky Cauldron (website)|The Leaky Cauldron]], it differed from MuggleCast with a more structured program, including various segments and involvement of more people on the Leaky Cauldron staff compared to MuggleCast. It also was the first Potter podcast to produce regular interviews with people directly involved with the books and films. The first show featured interviews with [[Stuart Craig]], art director of the films, as well as [[Bonnie Wright]], who plays [[Ginny Weasley]]. PotterCast has also interviewed [[Matthew Lewis (actor)|Matthew Lewis]] (the actor who portrays [[Neville Longbottom]]), [[Evanna Lynch]] ([[Luna Lovegood]]), [[Jamie Waylett]] ([[Vincent Crabbe]]), [[Rupert Grint]] ([[Ron Weasley]]), [[Chris Columbus (filmmaker)|Chris Columbus]], [[Alfonso Cuar\u00f3n]], [[Mike Newell (director)|Mike Newell]] (directors of the first four films), Arthur A. Levine and Cheryl Klein (editors of the books at [[Scholastic Corporation|Scholastic]]), and Rowling herself.<ref name=what-is-pc>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/pottercast/page/what|title=PotterCast is the Harry Potter podcast brought to you by The Leaky Cauldron|publisher=PotterCast|accessdate=27 February 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070102134107/http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/pottercast/page/what |archivedate = 2 January 2007|date=19 September 2002}}</ref>\n\nThe two sites are friendly rivals and have aired several combined episodes, which they call \"The Leaky Mug\", a separate podcast released on a separate feed from time to time. Live joint podcasts have been held in [[New York City]], [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]], and [[California]]. From time to time, hosts on one podcast will appear on their counterpart.<ref name=what-is-pc/>\n\nOther notable Harry Potter podcasts include ''[[Harry Potter and the Sacred Text]]'', in which the books are read as if they were a religious text, ''Witch Please'', which looks at the books through a feminist lens, and ''Potterotica'', in which actors read Harry Potter fan fiction aloud.<ref>{{cite web |title=Harry Potter podcasts that even muggles can love |url=https://www.cbc.ca/radio/podcastplaylist/harry-potter-podcasts-that-even-muggles-can-love-1.3992234 |website=[[CBC Radio]] |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Ragsdale |first1=Melissa |title=11 Harry Potter Podcasts Every Potterhead Needs In Their Life |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/11-harry-potter-podcasts-every-potterhead-needs-in-their-life-62902 |website=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Fan fiction==\nRowling has backed [[fan fiction]] stories on the Internet, stories written by fans that involve [[Harry Potter (character)|Harry Potter]] or other characters in the books.<ref name=fanfic-bbc>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3753001.stm|title=Rowling backs Potter fan fiction|work=BBC|date=27 May 2004|accessdate=14 January 2007 | first=Darren | last=Waters}}</ref> A March 2007 study showed that \"Harry Potter\" is the most searched-for fan fiction subject online.<ref name=most-searched-fanfiction>{{cite news|url=http://buzz.yahoo.com/buzzlog/67161/fantastic-fiction |title=Fantastic Fiction |date=20 March 2007 |accessdate=7 April 2007 |last=Hurd |first=Gordon |work=[[Yahoo!]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071222003119/http://buzz.yahoo.com/buzzlog/67161/fantastic-fiction |archivedate=22 December 2007 }}</ref> Some fans will use canon established in the books to write stories of past and future events in the ''Harry Potter'' world; others write stories that have little relation to the books other than the characters' names and the settings in which the fan fiction takes place. On [[FanFiction.Net]], there are over 817,000, while [[Archive of Our Own]] has  over 230,000 stories on Harry Potter {{As of|2020|4|lc=y|df=US}}. There are numerous websites devoted solely to Harry Potter fan fiction. Of these, according to rankings on Alexa.com, HarryPotterFanfiction.com has grown to be the most popular.\n\nA well-known work of fan fiction is The Shoebox Project, created by two [[LiveJournal]] users. Over 8500 people subscribe to the story so that they are alerted when new posts update the story. The authors' works, including this project, were featured in an article in ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' discussing the growth in popularity of fandoms.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/public/article/SB115836001321164886.html|title=Rewriting the Rules of Fiction|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|date=16 September 2007|accessdate=4 September 2007|last=Jurgensen|first=John}}</ref>\n\nThe current most reviewed piece of fanfiction, with over 25,000 reviews, is ''[[Harry Potter and the Methods of Rationality]]'' by [[Eliezer Yudkowsky]] writing under the pseudonym of Less Wrong.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fanfiction.net/s/5782108/1/Harry_Potter_and_the_Methods_of_Rationality |title=Harry Potter and the Methods of Rationality Chapter 1: A Day of Very Low Probability, a harry potter fanfic |publisher=FanFiction.Net |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://esr.ibiblio.org/?p=2100 |title=Harry Potter and the Methods of Rationality |publisher=Esr.ibiblio.org |date=6 July 2010 |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, the \"popular 'bad' fanfic\" ''[[My Immortal (fan fiction)|My Immortal]]'' was posted on [[FanFiction.Net]] by user \"Tara Gilesbie\".<ref name=\"guide\">{{cite book |title= The Ultimate Guide to the Harry Potter Fandom|last= Pyne|first= Erin |year= 2010|publisher= What The Flux Comics Publishing Inc. |isbn= 978-1-4507-4560-4|page= 126}}</ref><ref name=\"cracked\">{{cite web|url = http://www.cracked.com/funny-3085-my-immortal/|title=My Immortal|publisher= [[Cracked.com]]|accessdate = 9 May 2011}}</ref> It was deleted by the site's administrators in 2008,<ref name=\"cracked\"/> but not before amassing over eight thousand negative reviews.<ref name=\"guide\"/> It spawned a number of [[YouTube]] spoofs<ref name=\"guide\"/> and a number of imitators created \"sequels\" claiming to be the original Tara.<ref name=\"cracked\"/>\n\nIn 2007, a web-based novel, ''[[James Potter and the Hall of Elders' Crossing]]'', was written by a computer animator named George Lippert. The book was written as a supplement to fill the void after ''Deathly Hallows'', and received eventual approval from Rowling herself.<ref name=gnorm>{{cite web|title=On Eve of James Potter Sequel, Harry Potter fan Fiction Heats up: Unlikely Author Poised to Keep the Story Alive|publisher=PRWEB|year=2008|url=http://www.prweb.com/releases/2008/07/prweb1080574.htm|accessdate=20 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nRowling has said, \"I find it very flattering that people love the characters that much.\" She has adopted a positive position on fan fiction, unlike authors such as [[Anne McCaffrey]] or [[Anne Rice]] who discourage fans from writing about their books and have asked sites like FanFiction.Net to remove all stories of their works, requests honored by the site.<ref name=fanfic-bbc/> However, Rowling has been \"alarmed by pornographic or sexually explicit material clearly not meant for kids,\" according to Neil Blair, an attorney for her publisher. The attorneys have sent [[cease and desist]] letters to sites that host adult material.<ref name=fanfic-hpana>{{cite news|url=http://www.hpana.com/news.14252.html|title=Potter fans produce Potter fiction|publisher=HPANA|date=18 June 2003|accessdate=14 January 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060811000252/http://www.hpana.com/news.14252.html|archive-date=11 August 2006|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nPotter fan fiction also has a large following in the [[slash fiction]] genre, stories which feature sexual relationships that do not exist in the books (''[[Shipping (fandom)|shipping]]''), often portraying homosexual pairings.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://technology.guardian.co.uk/online/story/0,,853539,00.html|title=Fan fiction|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=5 December 2002|accessdate=14 January 2007|last=Pauli|first=Michelle | location=London}}</ref><ref name=potter-slash>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.om/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/chronicle/archive/2001/11/18/IN92578.DTL |page=D3 |title=Pottershots: The trouble with Harry |last=Noxon |first=Christopher |date=18 November 2001 |accessdate=14 April 2007 |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Famous pairings include Harry with [[Draco Malfoy]] or [[Cedric Diggory]], and [[Remus Lupin]] with [[Sirius Black]].<ref name=potter-slash/><ref name=observer-lumos>{{cite news|url=http://books.guardian.co.uk/departments/childrenandteens/story/0,,1838086,00.html|title=Harry Potter and the mystery of an academic obsession|date=6 August 2006|accessdate=27 July 2007|work=The Guardian|last=Cadwalladr|first=Carole | location=London}}</ref> Harry Potter slash has eroded some of the antipathy towards underage sexuality in the wider slash fandom.<ref name=\"WorldofYaoi\">McLelland, Mark. [http://ro.uow.edu.au/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1152&context=artspapers The World of Yaoi: The Internet, Censorship and the Global \u201cBoys\u2019 Love\u201d Fandom] ''[[The Australian Feminist Law Journal]]'', 2005.</ref>\n\nTracey \"T\" Proctor, a moderator of FictionAlley.org, a ''Harry Potter'' fanfiction website, said 'I don't really get into the children's aspect of it, but rather the teachers, the adult characters. I read someone once who said, \"If she didn't want us fantasizing about her characters, she needs to stop having these handsome men portraying them.\" And that's the truth: It's very hard not to look at Alan Rickman [Professor Severus Snape] and Jason Isaacs [Lucius Malfoy] and not get erotic thoughts. I have some fan fiction at Fiction Alley. You want to write stories about the characters that J.K. is not writing, about their love lives that you don't see in the book.'<ref>\"Petrosexuals.\" ''[[Riverfront Times]]''. 4 January 2006. p. [http://www.riverfronttimes.com/2006-01-04/news/petrosexuals/ 1]. Retrieved on 19 February 2013.</ref>\n\nIn November 2006, [[Jason Isaacs]], who plays [[Lucius Malfoy]] in the ''Potter'' films, said that he had read fan fiction about his character and gets \"a huge kick out of the more far-out stuff.\"<ref name=isaacs-hp-lex>{{cite news|url=http://www.hp-lexicon.org/about/films/lex-op-set-teaser.html|title=The Lexicon Visits The Magic Factory (part one)|date=24 November 2006|accessdate=14 January 2007|publisher=The [[Harry Potter Lexicon]]|last=VanderArk|first=Steve|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070113125007/http://www.hp-lexicon.org/about/films/lex-op-set-teaser.html|archivedate=13 January 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Discussion===\nPrior to the publication of ''[[Deathly Hallows]]'', much of the energy of the Potter fandom was devoted to speculation and debate about upcoming plot and character developments. To this end, clues from the earlier books and deliberate hints from [[J. K. Rowling]] (in interviews and on her website) were heavily scrutinised by fans. In particular, fan essays were published on websites such as [[Mugglenet]] (the \"world famous editorials\"), the [[Harry Potter Lexicon]] and [[The Leaky Cauldron (website)|The Leaky Cauldron]] (Scribbulus project) among others: offering theories, comment and analysis on all aspects of the series. The [[Yahoo]] discussion list [[Harry Potter for Grown Ups]] (founded in 1999) is also noteworthy for its detailed criticism and discussion of the Harry Potter books.\n\nSpeculation intensified with the July 2005 publication of ''[[Half-Blood Prince]]'' and the detailed post-publication interview given by Rowling to Mugglenet and The Leaky Cauldron.<ref>{{cite web|author=MuggleNet |url=http://www.mugglenet.com/jkrinterview.shtml |title=Emerson and Melissa's J.K. Rowling Interview Page 1 |publisher=MuggleNet |accessdate=16 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120612094057/http://www.mugglenet.com/jkrinterview.shtml |archivedate=12 June 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> Notably, DumbledoreIsNotDead.com sought to understand the events of the sixth book in a different way. (Rowling later confirmed, however&nbsp;\u2013 on 2 August 2006&nbsp;\u2013 that Dumbledore was, in fact, dead, humorously apologising to the website as she did so.)<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.hpana.com/news.19531.html | title=Dumbledore 'definitely' dead, says Rowling| date=3 August 2006}}</ref> A collection of essays, ''Who Killed Albus Dumbledore?: What Really Happened in Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince? Six Expert Harry Potter Detectives Examine the Evidence'', was published by Zossima Press in November 2006. Contributors included the Christian author [[John Granger]] and Joyce Odell of Red Hen Publications, whose own website contains numerous essays on the Potterverse and fandom itself.\n\nIn 2006, in advance of the arrival of the seventh Potter novel, five MuggleNet staff members co-authored the reference book ''Mugglenet.Com's What Will Happen in Harry Potter 7: Who Lives, Who Dies, Who Falls in Love and How Will the Adventure Finally End'', an anthology of unofficial fan predictions; while early in 2007, Leaky launched HarryPotterSeven.com, featuring \"roundups and predictions from some of the most knowledgeable fans online\" (including [[Steve Vander Ark]] of the Lexicon). Late additions to the fan scene (prior to the publication of ''[[Deathly Hallows]]'') included BeyondHogwarts.com (the successor to DumbledoreIsNotDead.com), which billed itself as \"the only ongoing online Harry Potter fan conference\", as well as Book7.co.uk, which offered a hypothetical \"evidence-based synopsis\" of the seventh novel. To this day, debate and reaction to the novels and films continues on web forums (including Mugglenet's Chamber of Secrets community and TLC's Leaky Lounge).\n\n==Fan film and television==\n{{main|Voldemort: Origins of the Heir}}\nA 2018 Italian fan-made [[prequel]] to the series, ''[[Voldemort: Origins of the Heir]]'', depicts the story of Tom Riddle's rise to power.<ref name=Echites2018>{{Cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/spettacoli/cinema/2018/01/16/news/voldemort-186609861/?ref=RHPPRT-BS-I0-C4-P1-S1.4-T1|title= CINEMA Le origini di Voldemort in un film tutto italiano|last=Echites|first=Giulia|work=[[Repubblica.it]]|access-date=17 January 2018|date=16 January 2018|language=it-IT}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/0/voldemort-origins-heir-review-fun-free-harry-potter-fan-film/|title=Voldemort: Origins of the Heir review: a fun-free Harry Potter fan film lifted by magical effects|last=Brown|first=Kat|date=2018|work=The Telegraph|access-date=21 January 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> The teaser trailer was released on in June 2017, receiving exceeded thirty million views in less than 48 hours on Facebook. The full movie was later released on YouTube on 13 January 2018, receiving over twelve million views in ten days.\n\n''[[Hermione Granger and the Quarter Life Crisis]]'' is an online TV series focused on Hermione Granger's life after Hogwarts.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.elle.com/uk/life-and-culture/culture/news/a33603/hermione-granger-quarter-life-crisis/|title=The side of Hermione you didn't get to see|date=2017-01-24|work=ELLE|access-date=2018-11-21|language=en-GB}}</ref> In the show, Granger, cast as a black woman played by Ashley Romans,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shadowandact.com/web-series-hermione-granger-and-the-quarter-life-crisis/|title='Hermione Granger and the Quarter Life Crisis' centers a black Hermione in a post-Hogwarts world|website=shadowandact.com|language=en|access-date=2018-11-21}}</ref> has broken up with Ron Weasley and moved to Los Angeles to reevaluate her life and choices.\n\n==Conventions==\n[[File:Sectus-midnight-wait.jpg|thumb|right|260px|Attendees of Sectus convention in London await the midnight release of ''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows'']]\n[[Fan conventions]] have been another way that the fandom has congregated. Conventions such as Prophecy, [[Mischief Management|LeakyCon]], Infinitus, Azkatraz, and Ascendio have maintained an academic emphasis, hosting professional keynote speakers as well as keeping the atmosphere playful and friendly. They have featured prominent members of the fandom such as Jennie Levine, owner of SugarQuill.net (Phoenix Rising, 2007); Melissa Anelli, current webmaster of The Leaky Cauldron (Phoenix Rising, 2007; Leakycon, 2009/2011/2012); Sue Upton, former Senior Editor of the Leaky Cauldron (Prophecy, 2007); Heidi Tandy, founder of Fiction Alley (Prophecy, 2007), Paul and Joe DeGeorge of the wizard rock band [[Harry and the Potters]] (along with several other more well-known Wizard Rock bands such as The Remus Lupins, The Parselmouths, Ministry of Magic, and The Whomping Willows) (see [[#Wizard rock|below]])<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/?articleID=9786|date=1 May 2007|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron|title=Prophecy Announces Keynote Speakers|last=Anelli|first=Melissa|accessdate=1 May 2007}}</ref> (Prophecy, 2007; Leakycon, 2009/2011/2012), Andrew Slack, founder of The [[Harry Potter Alliance]], and [[StarKid Productions|StarKid]], the cast of the fan made musicals \"A Very Potter Musical\", \"A Very Potter Sequel\", and \"A Very Potter Senior Year\".\n\nStill, the conventions try to attract the fandom with other fun-filled ''Potter''-centric activities, often more interactive, such as wizarding chess, water [[Quidditch]], a showing of the [[Harry Potter (film)|''Harry Potter'' films]],<ref name=lumos-events>{{cite web|url=http://lumos2006.org/schedule.shtml|title=Lumos 2006: Programming&nbsp;\u2014 Schedule|accessdate=3 January 2007|publisher=Lumos 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070209135552/http://lumos2006.org/schedule.shtml|archivedate=9 February 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> or local cultural immersions. Live podcasts are often recorded during these events,<ref>{{cite web|title=MuggleCast Episodes 234 & 235 |url=http://www.mugglenet.com/mugglecast/episodes_page17.php |work=MuggleCast |publisher=MuggleNet |accessdate=12 December 2012 |date=18 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130227081228/http://www.mugglenet.com/mugglecast/episodes_page17.php |archivedate=27 February 2013 }}</ref> and live Wizard Rock shows have become a fairly large part of recent conventions.<ref>{{cite web|last=Anelli|first=Melissa|title=LeakyCon 2011 Announces Wizard Rock Lineup|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/2010/10/5/leakycon-2011-announces-wizard-rock-lineup|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron|accessdate=12 December 2012|date=5 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ascendio Wrocks! |url=http://hp2012.org/?page_id=837 |publisher=Ascendio 2012/HPEF |accessdate=6 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120417130540/http://hp2012.org/?page_id=837 |archivedate=17 April 2012 }}</ref> Members of the ''Harry Potter'' cast have been brought in for the conferences; actors such as [[Evanna Lynch]] (Luna Lovegood) and [[Chris Rankin|Christopher Rankin]] (Percy Weasley), along with several others, have appeared to give live Q&A sessions and keynote presentations about the series.<ref>{{cite web|last=Anelli|first=Melissa|title=Meet the Deathly Hallows Actors at Leakycon 2011|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/2011/6/2/meet-the-new-potter-actors-at-leakycon-2011|publisher=The Leaky Cauldron|accessdate=12 December 2012|date=2 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to fandom-specific programming, LeakyCon 2011 and 2012 have hosted LitDays (as well as incorporating the many fandoms ''Harry Potter'' fans have branched into since the ending of the series). LitDays are full of programming with authors, agents, and editors. A few key examples are [[John Green (author)|John Green]], author of the award-winning young adult novels ''[[The Fault in Our Stars]]'' and ''[[Looking for Alaska]]''; [[Scott Westerfeld]], author of the ''Uglies'' series and ''Leviathan''; and [[David Levithan]], author of ''Nick & Norah's Infinite Playlist'' and ''The Lover's Dictionary''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leakycon 2011 Programming|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/leakycon/leakycon2011programming.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626032840/http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/leakycon/leakycon2011programming.pdf |archivedate=2011-06-26|accessdate=12 December 2012|pages=2\u20134}}</ref>\n\nThese conventions are now incorporating the recently opened theme park The Wizarding World of Harry Potter<ref>{{cite web|title=The Wizarding World of Harry Potter|url=http://www.universalorlando.com/harrypotter/|accessdate=12 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121211184519/http://www.universalorlando.com/HarryPotter/|archive-date=11 December 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> into their itinerary, built inside Universal's Island of Adventure in Orlando, Florida. At the ''Harry Potter'' fan conventions Infinitus 2010,<ref>{{cite web|last=Brigante|first=Ricky|title=Night of a Thousand Wizards draws biggest Harry Potter fans to Universal Orlando's Wizarding World at Infinitus 2010|url=http://www.insidethemagic.net/2010/07/night-of-a-thousand-wizards-draws-biggest-harry-potter-fans-to-universal-orlandos-wizarding-world-at-infinitus-2010/|accessdate=12 December 2012|date=23 July 2010}}</ref> LeakyCon 2011,<ref>{{cite web|title=Leakycon 2011 Programming |url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/leakycon/leakycon2011programming.pdf |publisher=The-Leaky-Cauldron.org |accessdate=6 December 2012 |page=5 |year=2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626032840/http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/leakycon/leakycon2011programming.pdf |archivedate=26 June 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Roseboom|first=Matt|title=Wizarding World of Harry Potter Will be 'Open at the Close' for a Special Fan Event|url=http://attractionsmagazine.com/blog/2011/05/16/wizarding-world-of-harry-potter-will-be-open-at-the-close-for-special-fan-event/|accessdate=12 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126053342/http://attractionsmagazine.com/blog/2011/05/16/wizarding-world-of-harry-potter-will-be-open-at-the-close-for-special-fan-event/|archive-date=26 January 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and Ascendio 2012,<ref>{{cite web|title=Night of A Thousand Wizards 2 |url=http://hp2012.org/?page_id=864 |publisher=Ascendio 2012 |accessdate=6 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121007181615/http://hp2012.org/?page_id=864 |archivedate=7 October 2012 }}</ref> special events were held at the theme park dedicated to the series. These are after-hours events for convention attendees who purchased tickets to experience and explore the park by themselves. The event included talks given by creators of the park, free food and [[butterbeer]], and live wizard rock shows inside the park.\n\n==Festivals==\nIn addition to conventions, Harry Potter fandom has further expanded to town festivals, including the Chestertown Harry Potter Festival (Maryland),<ref>{{cite web|title=Chestertown Harry Potter Festival |url=http://chestertownhpfest.org/|accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> the Chestnut Hill Harry Potter Festival (Philadelphia),<ref>{{cite web|title=Chestnut HIll Harry Potter Festival|url=http://chestnuthillpa.com/events/harry-potter-festival-2016/|accessdate=15 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160912173458/http://chestnuthillpa.com/events/harry-potter-festival-2016/|archivedate=12 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  Edgerton's Harry Potter Festival (Wisconsin),<ref>{{cite web|title=Edgerton's Harry Potter Festival|url=http://www.harrypotterfestival.com/|accessdate=15 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160712122715/http://www.harrypotterfestival.com/|archive-date=12 July 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and the Spellbound Festival (Michigan, 2016; Ontario, 2018; New York, 2019),<ref>{{cite web|title=Spellbound Festival |url=http://stbonavenue.com/spellbound-festival/|accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> among others.\n\n==Religions==\nThe Harry Potter fandom has also led to the development of at least one religion. The religion of 'Snapeism' was active from 2005-2011. The Snapists (popularly known as the Snapewives) worshipped the Severus Snape character.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Alderton|first1=Zoe|title='Snapewives' and 'Snapeism': A Fiction-Based Religion within the Harry Potter Fandom|journal=Religions|date=3 March 2014|volume=5|issue=1|pages=219\u2013267|doi=10.3390/rel5010219|doi-access=free}}</ref> The Snapists were mocked by the majority of the fandom, especially the JournalFen community 'fandom_wank', for their unorthodox belief systems. Nevertheless, recent scholarship has argued for the validity of fandom faiths.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Davidsen|first1=Markus A.|title=Fiction-Based Religion: Conceptualising a New Category Against History-Based Religion and Fandom|journal=Culture and Religion|volume=14|issue=4|pages=378\u2013395|doi=10.1080/14755610.2013.838798|year=2013|url=https://openaccess.leidenuniv.nl/bitstream/handle/1887/48123/Davidsen2013ConceptualisingFiction-basedReligion_Postprint.pdf?sequence=1}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Cusack|first1=Carole|title=Invented Religions: Imagination, Fiction and Faith|date=2010|publisher=Ashgate|location=Farnham}}</ref>\n\nThe Snapists exist within a context of 'canon scepticism' - the belief that Rowling is a flawed interpreter of the Harry Potter universe who misrepresents the objective reality of certain characters and plot developments.<ref name=\"Alderton Snapewives\">{{cite journal|last1=Alderton|first1=Zoe|title='Snapewives' and 'Snapeism': A Fiction-Based Religion within the Harry Potter Fandom|journal=Religions|date=3 March 2014|volume=5|issue=1|page=224|doi=10.3390/rel5010219|doi-access=free}}</ref> The Snapists believe that Rowling has misinterpreted Snape and disrespected him as a character. They also feel that Snape can contact them and provide them with help and guidance in life.\n\n==\"Ship debates\"==\n{{further|Shipping (fandom)#Harry Potter fandom}}\nIn the fandom the word \"ship\" and its derivatives like \"shipping\" or \"shipper\" are commonly used as shorthand for the word \"relationship.\"\n\nThe ''Harry Potter'' series generated ship debates with supporters of the prospective relationship between [[Harry Potter (character)|Harry Potter]] and his close female friend [[Hermione Granger]] at odds with supporters of Hermione ending up instead with [[Ron Weasley]], close friend of both, as well as  supporters of Harry ending up with [[Ginny Weasley]], Ron's younger sister.\n\nQuotes from Rowling which seemed to contradict the possibility of Harry ending up with Hermione were usually countered by claiming them to be deliberate obfuscations designed to lure astute observation off-course (though such claims were far from undisputed, given that these allegedly vague quotes included such phrases as \"[Harry and Hermione] are very platonic friends\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accio-quote.org/articles/1999/1099-pressclubtransc.htm |title=1999: Accio Quote!, the largest archive of J.K. Rowling interviews on the web |publisher=Accio-quote.org |date=20 October 1999 |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref> and were repeated on at least three different occasions).\n\nAn interview with J.K. Rowling conducted by fansite webmasters Emerson Spartz ([[MuggleNet]]) and Melissa Anelli ([[The Leaky Cauldron (website)|The Leaky Cauldron]]) shortly after the book's release turned out to be quite controversial. During the interview Spartz commented that Harry/Hermione shippers were \"delusional\", to which Rowling chuckled, though making it clear that she did not share the sentiment and that the Harry/Hermione fans were \"still valued members of her readership\". This incident resulted in an uproar among Harry/Hermione shippers. The uproar was loud enough to merit an article in the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]''.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2005/08/03/DDG0RE1DDI1.DTL | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | first=Neva | last=Chonin | title=If you're an obsessed Harry Potter fan, Voldemort isn't the problem. It's Hermione versus Ginny | date=24 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nRowling's attitude towards the shipping phenomenon has varied between amused and bewildered to frustrated, as she revealed in that interview. She explained:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accio-quote.org/articles/2005/0705-tlc_mugglenet-anelli-2.htm |title=2005: Accio Quote!, the largest archive of J.K. Rowling interviews on the web |publisher=Accio-quote.org |date=16 July 2005 |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|Well, you see, I'm a relative newcomer to the world of shipping, because for a long time, I didn't go on the net and look up Harry Potter. A long time. Occasionally I had to, because there were weird news stories or something that I would have to go and check, because I was supposed to have said something I hadn\u2019t said. I had never gone and looked at fan sites, and then one day I did and oh&nbsp;\u2014 my&nbsp;\u2014 god. Five hours later or something, I get up from the computer shaking slightly [all laugh]. 'What is going on?\u2019 And it was during that first mammoth session that I met the shippers, and it was a most extraordinary thing. I had no idea there was this huge underworld seething beneath me.}}\n\nIn a later posting on MuggleNet, Spartz explained:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mugglenet.com/newsfusion/fullnews.php?id=972 |title=THE INTERVIEW! Part two |publisher=MuggleNet |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028134002/http://www.mugglenet.com/newsfusion/fullnews.php?id=972 |archive-date=28 October 2007 |url-status=dead |accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|My comments weren't directed at the shippers who acknowledged that Harry/Hermione was a long shot but loved the idea of them together. It was directed at the \"militant\" shippers who ''insisted'' that there was overwhelming canon proof and that everyone else was too blind to see it. You were delusional; you saw what you wanted to see and you have no one to blame for that but yourselves.}}\n\nRowling has continued to make references, less humorous and more, to the severity of the shipper conflicts. In one instance she has joked about trying to think of ways of proving to Emerson, when inviting him for the aforementioned interview, that it was really her and not \"some angry Harry/Hermione shipper trying to lure him down a dark alleyway\";<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/extrastuff_view.cfm?id=21 |title=Meeting Melissa and Emerson |website=[[J. K. Rowling]] |archive-date=16 March 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060316221055/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/extrastuff_view.cfm?id=21 |url-status=dead |accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref> In another, she has described her impression of the Harry Potter fandom's shipping debates as \"cyber gang warfare\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accio-quote.org/articles/2006/0801-radiocityreading1.html |title=2006: Accio Quote!, the largest archive of J.K. Rowling interviews on the web |publisher=Accio-quote.org |date=1 August 2006 |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nRowling stated in an interview in February 2014 in ''Wonderland'' Magazine that she thought that realistically Hermione and Ron had \"too much fundamental incompatibility.\" She stated that Hermione and Ron were written together \"as a form of wish fulfillment\" as way to reconcile a relationship she herself was once in. She went on to say that perhaps with marriage counseling Ron and Hermione would have been all right.<ref>West, Kelly. [https://www.cinemablend.com/pop/What-J-K-Rowling-Actually-Said-About-Hermione-Relationships-With-Ron-Harry-62153.html \"What J.K. Rowling Actually Said About Hermione's Relationships With Ron And Harry\"], Cinema Blend, 7 February 2014. Retrieved on 2 October 2014.</ref> She also went on to say in a talk at Exeter University that Harry's love for Ginny is true, thereby denying any potential canon relationship between Harry and Hermione.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://filthysquib.tumblr.com/post/76130596653/ive-just-got-back-from-the-jk-rowling-lecture |title = Tumblr}}</ref>\n\n===Other relationships===\nOn a less intense scale, other relationships have been doted upon in the fandom from suggestive hints or explicit statements throughout canon, such as those between Draco Malfoy and [[Pansy Parkinson]], [[Harry Potter's]] parents [[James Potter (character)|James Potter]] and [[Lily Evans]], [[Rubeus Hagrid]] and [[Olympe Maxime]], or [[Percy Weasley]] and [[Minor Ravenclaws#Penelope Clearwater|Penelope Clearwater]], or Rose Granger-Weasley and Scorpius Malfoy. A potential relationship between [[Neville Longbottom]] and [[Luna Lovegood]] was originally dispelled by Rowling,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/rumours_view.cfm?id=24 |title=Luna and Neville will hook up in HP&THBP |work=J. K. Rowling Official Site |last=Rowling |first=J. K. |accessdate=14 January 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070204111459/http://www.jkrowling.com/textonly/en/rumours_view.cfm?id=24 |archivedate=4 February 2007 }}</ref> though she later retracted this and said she noticed a slight attraction between them in ''Deathly Hallows''.<ref name=wild-about-harry>{{cite news|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/19959323/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070801083035/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/19959323/|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 August 2007|date=25 July 2007|accessdate=26 July 2007|publisher=[[MSNBC]]|last=Brown|first=Jen|title=Finished Potter? Rowling tells what happened next.}}</ref> Some couples, besides Harry and Ginny and Ron and Hermione, have been explicitly stated in the series: [[Bill Weasley]] and [[Fleur Delacour]] are married in ''Deathly Hallows'' after dating throughout ''Half-Blood Prince''.<ref>Rowling, J. K. (2007). ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows]]'' (in English). [[London]]: [[Bloomsbury Publishing|Bloomsbury]]/[[New York City]]: [[Scholastic Corporation|Scholastic]], et al. UK {{ISBN|0-7475-9105-9}}/US {{ISBN|0-545-01022-5}}, chapter 8.</ref> In ''Half-Blood Prince'', [[Nymphadora Tonks]] keeps her feelings for [[Remus Lupin]] to herself, but remains depressed when he refuses her advances; he feels that his being a werewolf would not create a safe relationship.<ref>Rowling, J. K. (2005). ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]'' (in English). [[London]]: [[Bloomsbury Publishing|Bloomsbury]]/[[New York City]]: [[Scholastic Corporation|Scholastic]], et al. UK {{ISBN|0-7475-8108-8}}/US {{ISBN|0-439-78454-9}}, chapter 29.</ref> Tonks professes her love for him at the end of the book, and she and Lupin have been married by the beginning of ''Deathly Hallows'' and have a son 'Teddy' later in the book.<ref>Rowling, ''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows'', chapter 1.</ref> Other couples, such as Harry and Draco or Lupin and [[Sirius Black]], are favorites among fans who read fan fiction about them. There is also debate about Lily and Severus vs. James.<ref name=potter-slash/><ref name=observer-lumos/>\n\n==Roleplaying games==\n[[Image:MuggleQuidditch.jpg|thumb|left|270px|[[Millikin University]] students at their biannual [[Muggle Quidditch]] tournament, a form of live action roleplay.]]\n[[Roleplaying]] is a central feature of the Harry Potter fandom. There are two primary forms: internet-based roleplay and live-action roleplay, or [[LARP]].\n\nLARPing often involves re-enacting or creating an original Quidditch team. Match rules and style of play vary among fandom events, but they are generally kept as close as possible to the sport envisioned by Rowling. The 2006 Lumos symposium included a Quidditch tournament played in water.<ref name=lumos-water-quidditch-rules>{{cite web|url=http://lumos2006.org/quidditch.shtml|title=Water Quidditch|publisher=Lumos 2006|accessdate=16 February 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070104124150/http://lumos2006.org/quidditch.shtml|archivedate=4 January 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> More common are ground-based games such as the handball style developed by USA Team Handball and featured at the [[MuggleNet]]-sponsored ''Spellbound'' event, as well as the [[Muggle Quidditch]] style played intramurally at [[Millikin University]] (at left).<ref>{{cite web|publisher=MuggleNet |url=http://www.mugglenet.com/spellbound.shtml |title=Spellbound! |accessdate=29 June 2006 |date=6 June 2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060906111731/http://www.mugglenet.com/spellbound.shtml |archivedate=6 September 2006 }}</ref> This version of quidditch has grown past intramural play, is far from LARPing, and has an international governing body, the IQA.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=IQA|url=http://www.internationalquidditch.org| title=The International Quidditch Association| accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nInternet-based roleplay tries to simulate the Hogwarts experience.  Most{{which|date=March 2013}} sites are forum-based, emphasizing taking classes taught by staff members in order for the players to earn points for their respective houses. Some{{which|date=March 2013}} internet-based roleplay sites go more in depth into canon and storylines, and do not specifically rely on posting as the only method for gaining house points while others{{which|date=March 2013}} have expanded to include activities such as Quidditch, dueling, and board-wide plots. Hogwarts-school.net (est. 2000), for example, is a forum-based roleplaying game which allows players to take classes, engage in extracurriculars, and also has many options for adult characters in St. Mungos, the Daily Prophet, and the Ministry of Magic.\n\n2007 saw the launch of World of Hogwarts,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldofhogwarts.org/intro.htm |title=Introduction |publisher=The World of Hogwarts |accessdate=16 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120623195942/http://www.worldofhogwarts.org/intro.htm |archivedate=23 June 2012 }}</ref> a completely free [[MMORPG]] [[Harry Potter]] roleplaying game in [[Second Life]], set ten years after the Battle of [[Hogwarts]]. Here, roleplayers can create an avatar and interact with other students, attend lessons organized by other roleplayers, play [[Quidditch]], sit for their exams, earn and lose points for their house, visit [[Hogsmeade]], [[Diagon Alley]] and the Forbidden Forest, get a job at the [[Ministry of Magic]], explore several secret passages within the castle, and even immerse themselves into intricate and well-composed storyline plots that have, through time, grown into the canon rules of the game.\n\nA website created by ISO Interactive, called the Chamber of Chat is a free online interactive virtual world under a [[Massively multiplayer online game|MMO]] format. Although not a full [[MMORPG]] format, Chamber of Chat is set up with 3D virtual chatrooms and avatars where fans can socially interact with each other in [[Pictionary]] and Harry Potter [[Trivia]]l games or participate in discussion groups about Harry Potter or Film media or perform plays as a theater group to other fans as audience. They hold special community event such as Harry Potters Birthday or Halloween and have seasonal house competitions.  Fans are able to create their own avatars, collect or be rewarded coins to purchase furniture items for their own \"clubhouse\". However, the website emphasizes more social interaction between fans' avatars to stimulate the Hogwarts student experience. \"Chamber of Chat is a graphical Social Virtual World with a few [[Facebook]] plug-ins. The Harry Potter Virtual World is designed for fans. This give users the feeling that they are interacting in the actual 3D world. You can hang out with other students, relax in the common room, mingle at the pub, play games like Pictionary and even download cool looking wallpapers.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chamberofchat.com/ |title=Chamber of Chat Harry Potter Interactive 3D World |publisher=Chamberofchat.com |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref> On 19 April 2007, Chamber of Chat was awarded [[Adobe Systems|Adobe]] Site of the day. Chamber of chat has also been awarded a place among the SmartFoxServer Showcase. \"Chamber of Chat is an MMO community inspired to the magic worlds of the Harry Potter saga. The application is a great example of integration between Director/Shockwave (client) and SmartFoxServer PRO.\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smartfoxserver.com/showcase/ |title=massive multiplayer game server for Flash, Unity 3D, iPhone/iPad and Android games, MMO, virtual worlds and communities |publisher=SmartFoxServer |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref> Chamber of Chat has been a long time associated branch of The Leaky network and although as part of the network with [[The Leaky Cauldron (website)|The Leaky Cauldron]], [[Pottercast]] and \"Ask [[Peeves]]\" search engine, it was ranked number two behind [[Indiana Jones|Indiana Jones's]] TheRaider.Net out of 25 essential fansites of \"The Best of the Web\" by [[Entertainment Weekly]] in December 2007.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20167049_24,00.html | work=Entertainment Weekly | title=25 Essential Fansites}}</ref>\n\nOther sites use modified versions of [[phpBB]] that allow for a certain level of [[interactive]] roleplaying and are what is commonly referred to as \"[[Play-by-post role-playing game|forum-based roleplaying]]\". Interactive gaming can include [[player versus player]] features, a form of currency for making purchases in stores, and [[non-player characters]] such as monsters that must be fought to gain levels and experience points. However, these features are more prevalent in games that are not forum-based. Advancement in such games is usually dependent on live chat, multiplayer cooperation, and fighting as opposed to taking classes or simply posting to earn points for one's \"house\"; like at Hogwarts, players in forum-based games are sometimes sorted into a different group distinguishing different values within a person.\n\nRoleplaying also occurs in [[Improv comedy|long-form improvisational]] theater. Several American and British improv troupes are devoted to the Potter genre. These include Melbourne's ''[https://www.improvisedpotter.com.au/ Completely Improvised Potter] London's [[Potted Potter]]'' and Los Angeles's ''[http://harrypotterimprov.com/ The Show That Shall Not Be Named].''\n\n==Iconic landmarks tours==\n[[Image:Glenfinnan Viaduct, Scotland.jpg|200px|right|thumb|The [[Glenfinnan viaduct]], which the [[Hogwarts Express]] passes over when it travels to Hogwarts in the films.]]\nSome travel agencies have organised a subdivision to create tours specifically highlighting iconic landmarks in the world of ''Harry Potter''. HP Fan Trips, offered by Beyond Boundaries Travel since 2004 in conjunction with fan site [[HPANA]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hpfantrips.com/about/|title=About HP Fan Trips|publisher=HP Fan Trips|accessdate=21 April 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070506200724/http://hpfantrips.com/about/|archive-date=6 May 2007|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=wp-hp-tours>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/12/29/AR2006122900440.html|title=On Holiday With Harry Potter|work=The Washington Post|date=31 December 2006|accessdate=21 April 2007|last=Sachs|first=Andrea}}</ref> was designed by and for fans of the series, and tours noteworthy ''Potter''-related locations in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news|title=Firm conjures up a host of Harry Potter-theme tours|work=Daily Herald (Arlington Heights, IL)|last=Hobica|first=George|author2=Kim Liang Tan|date=18 March 2007|page=2}}</ref> Since 2004, they have exclusively chartered steam locomotive [[GWR 4900 Class 5972 Olton Hall|#5972 Olton Hall]], the locomotive used in the films as the [[Hogwarts Express]], as well as the carriages labeled as such and seen in the movies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hpfantrips.com/2007/oltonhall/oltonhall.cfm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070302091514/http://www.hpfantrips.com/2007/oltonhall/oltonhall.cfm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2 March 2007 |title=HP Fan Trips 2007 Exclusive Train Ride |publisher=HP Fan Trips |accessdate=21 April 2007 }}</ref> The travel agency Your Man in Europe began hosting Magical Tours in 2006, in conjunction with fan site [[MuggleNet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://magicaltours.org/contest-rules.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070328193710/http://magicaltours.org/contest-rules.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=28 March 2007 |title=2007 MuggleNet, Magical Tours, and Alivan's CONTEST RULES |publisher=Magical Tours |accessdate=15 April 2007 }}</ref> They offer four different tours through England and Scotland.\n\n[[Image:Alnwick Castle - Northumberland - 140804.jpg|250px|left|thumb|[[Alnwick Castle]], the castle used for filming exterior shots of [[Hogwarts]] in the [[Harry Potter (film series)|''Potter'' films]].]]\nThese tours primarily feature locations used for shooting in the [[Harry Potter (film)|films]], though some trips include a Chinese restaurant in Edinburgh, which was once Nicholson's Cafe, where Rowling wrote much of the manuscript for ''[[Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone]]'', and [[Edinburgh Castle]], where Rowling read from the sixth book on the night of its release to an audience of children.<ref name=wp-hp-tours/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/features/20050715-1930-potter-castle.html|title=Lucky fans hear J.K. Rowling read at Edinburgh castle|date=15 July 2005|accessdate=21 April 2007|last=McAloon|first=Catherine|work=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080624230415/http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/features/20050715-1930-potter-castle.html|archivedate=24 June 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Filming locations visited include [[Alnwick Castle]], where some exterior locations of [[Hogwarts]] are shot, places in [[Fort William, Highland|Fort William]], Scotland; [[Glen Nevis]], Scotland; the [[Glenfinnan viaduct]]; [[Christ Church Cathedral, Oxford|Christ Church Cathedral]] in [[Oxford]] and the Cloisters located within [[New College, Oxford]].<ref name=wp-hp-tours/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/oxford/harry_potter/oxford_tour.shtml|title=Harry Potter video|work=BBC|accessdate=21 April 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Wizard rock==\n{{Main|Wizard rock}}\n[[Image:Harry and the Potters HM.JPG|right|thumb|250px|[[Harry and the Potters]] perform at the [[Horace Mann School]] in [[Riverdale, Bronx]], [[New York (state)|New York]].]]\n'''Wizard music''' (sometimes shorthanded as '''Wrock''') is a musical movement dating from 2000 in [[Massachusetts]] with Harry and the Potters, though it has grown internationally<ref name=poststan>{{cite news|url=http://www.syracuse.com/articles/cny/index.ssf?/base/living-3/118492494174900.xml&coll=1|title=Wizard Rock|publisher=[[The Post-Standard]]|date=20 July 2007|accessdate=31 July 2007|last=Loftus|first=Meghan|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071007095010/http://www.syracuse.com/articles/cny/index.ssf?%2Fbase%2Fliving-3%2F118492494174900.xml&coll=1|archivedate=7 October 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=279730 |title=The unexpected wizards of rock and roll |date=20 July 2007 |accessdate=31 July 2007 |publisher=[[MSN]] |last=Davies |first=Shaun |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120525193856/news.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=279730 |archivedate=25 May 2012 }}</ref> and has expanded to at least 750 bands.<ref>[http://wizrocklopedia.com/index.php/band-listings/ Wizrocklopedia band listings] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820100938/http://wizrocklopedia.com/index.php/band-listings |date=20 August 2008 }}</ref> Wrock bands mostly consist of young musicians that write and perform songs about the ''Harry Potter'' universe,<ref name=yule-ball-philly>{{cite news|url=http://articles.philly.com/2006-11-28/entertainment/25406043_1_whomping-willows-potter-phenomenon-fifth-book|title=Yule Ball rolls into Philly Show spotlights Harry Potter-themed rock|last=Brady|first=Shaun|publisher=[[Philadelphia Daily News]]|date=28 November 2006|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Business/FunMoney/Story?id=3371717&page=1|title=Harry Potter 'Wrockers' Conjure Musical Magic|date=13 July 2007|accessdate=31 July 2007|publisher=[[ABC News]]|last=Humphries|first=Rachel}}</ref> and these songs are often written from the point of view of a particular character in the books, usually the character who features in the band's name. If they are performing live, they may also [[cosplay]], or dress as, that character.<ref name=handp-boston-globe>{{cite news|url=https://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2004/09/16/sibling_musicians_bring_out_the_punk_in_harry_potter/|last=Sweeney|first=Emily|title=Sibling musicians bring out the 'punk' in Harry Potter|date=16 September 2004|accessdate=26 January 2007|publisher=The Boston Globe}}</ref>\n\nIn contrast to mainstream bands that have some songs incorporating literary references among a wider repertoire of music (notably [[Led Zeppelin]] to ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]''),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fortwayne.com/mld/newssentinel/living/16381778.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070330064614/http://www.fortwayne.com/mld/newssentinel/living/16381778.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=30 March 2007 |title=Four reasons you should raid your parents' music collection |date=4 January 2007 |accessdate=26 January 2007 |publisher=Fort Wayne News Sentinel |last=Gleason |first=Janelle }}</ref> wizard rock bands take their inspiration entirely from the ''Harry Potter'' universe.<ref name=handp-boston-globe/> In preserving the promotion of reading, too, bands like to perform in libraries, bookstores, and schools.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eskimolabs.com/hp/band.htm |title=Harry and the Potters: The Band |publisher=[[Harry and the Potters]] |accessdate=27 February 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070227215243/http://www.eskimolabs.com/hp/band.htm |archivedate=27 February 2007 }}</ref> The bands have also performed at the fan conventions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/books/feature/2007/06/01/phoenix_rising/|title=Potterpalooza|date=1 June 2007|accessdate=9 August 2007|last=Traister|first=Rebecca|publisher=Salon.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509155513/http://www.salon.com/books/feature/2007/06/01/phoenix_rising/|archivedate=9 May 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Documentaries==\n\n===''We Are Wizards''===\n'''''We Are Wizards''''' is a feature-length documentary by [[Josh Koury]] about the ''Harry Potter'' fandom. It features Wizard rock bands [[Harry and the Potters]], [[Draco and the Malfoys]], The Hungarian Horntails, and The Whomping Willows. The film also features [[Heather Lawver]], [[Melissa Anelli]], and [[Brad Neely]].<ref>[http://www.wearewizards-themovie.com/ We Are Wizards - The Movie] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080325134913/http://www.wearewizards-themovie.com/ |date=25 March 2008 }}</ref> ''We Are Wizards'' had its World Premiere at the SXSW film festival in 2008, then traveled to 20 film festivals worldwide.  The film opened theatrically in 5 cities on 14 November 2008.  The film can be seen on Hulu.com, and DVD.\n\n===''The Fandom Fan Diaries: Wizard's Gone W!ld''===\n'''''The Fandom Fan Diaries: Wizard's Gone W!ld''''' is a documentary web series that is based on fandom submissions. The producers Miranda Marshall and Amy Henderson starting accepting video submissions in early March 2009 and plan to accept them through 2013. ''WiZarDs Gone W!LD'' is affiliated with ''The Fan Book of HP Fans'', yet another fandom project based on submissions that has recently extended its submission deadline date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.facebook.com/home.php?#/group.php?gid=53471403919&ref=ts |title=The Fan Book of HP Fans *A Fan Project* |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref><ref>http://www.wizardsgonewild.webs.com {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111016135818/http://wizardsgonewild.webs.com/ |date=16 October 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===''The Wizard Rockumentary''===\n'''''The Wizard Rockumentary: A Movie about Rocking and Rowling''''' is a feature documentary chronicling the rise of Harry Potter tribute bands. Producers Megan and Mallory Schuyler travelled around the United States compiling interviews and concert footage of bands including [[Harry and the Potters]], [[Draco and the Malfoys]], The Remus Lupins, The Whomping Willow, The Moaning Myrtles, Roonil Wazlib, Snidget, and The Hermione Crookshanks Experience. The film was released in April 2008 and has screened in libraries around the country. The producers are currently negotiating broadcast and home video rights.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wizardrockumentary.com/about.html |title=About Us |publisher=Wizardrockumentary.com |accessdate=16 June 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206033559/http://www.wizardrockumentary.com/about.html |archive-date=6 February 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===''Proyecto Patronus''===\n'''''Project Patronus: magic of a generation''''' (''Proyecto Patronus: la magia de una generaci\u00f3n'') is a Spanish documentary based on the Harry Potter saga. It covers the franchise's influence on a generation of young people, and deals with the multiple [[values]], such as friendship, love, courage and respect, which are reflected in the books. Numerous professionals in [[psychology]] and [[pedagogy]] who have studied the significance of the saga appear. The film was released in 2016 and has screened in film festivals around Spain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elmundo.es/enredados/2015/09/07/55ed602722601de96a8b457a.html |title=Proyecto Patronus |publisher=Elmundo.com |accessdate=7 September 2015|date=7 September 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Health==\nIn 2003, Dr. Howard J. Bennett coined the term \"Hogwarts headache\" in a letter to the [[New England Journal of Medicine]] shortly after the release of the longest book in the series, ''[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix|Order of the Phoenix]]''.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.medicinenet.com/script/main/art.asp?articlekey=25035 |title = Definition of Hogwarts headache}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/uk/newsid_2661000/2661257.stm|title=Potter book five: on sale on 21 June|date=15 January 2003|accessdate=16 April 2007|work=BBC Newsround}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/books/news/2005-07-13-potter-rumors_x.htm|title=Rumors run wild about 'Harry'|date=13 July 2005|accessdate=16 April 2007|work=[[USA Today]]|last=Memmott|first=Carol}}</ref> He described it as a mild condition, a [[tension headache]] possibly accompanied by neck or wrist pains, caused by unhealthily long reading sessions of ''Harry Potter''. The symptoms resolved themselves within days of finishing the book. His prescription of taking reading breaks was rejected by two of the patients on which he discovered this headache.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Hogwarts Headaches&nbsp;\u2014 Misery for Muggles|first=Howard J.|last=Bennett|date=30 October 2003|journal=[[New England Journal of Medicine]]|volume=349|issue=18|pmid=14585953|doi=10.1056/NEJM200310303491821|page=1779}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1056/NEJM200310303491821| pmid=14585953| title=Hogwarts Headaches \u2014 Misery for Muggles| journal=New England Journal of Medicine| volume=349| issue=18| pages=1779| year=2003| last1=Bennett| first1=Howard J.}}</ref>\n\nResearchers at [[John Radcliffe Hospital]] in [[Oxford]] found in 2005 that the admission rate of children with traumatic injuries to the city's [[emergency department|ER]]s plummeted on the publication weekends of both ''[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix|Order of the Phoenix]]'' and ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince|Half-Blood Prince]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/03/health/03safe.html?ex=1185508800&en=1b1e26eb8831fcc9&ei=5070 |title=Safety: With Harry Potter, Injuries Dip Like Magic |first=Eric |last=Nagourney |work=[[New York Times]] |accessdate=25 July 2007 | date=3 January 2006}}</ref> This was due to the volume of children reading Harry Potter rather than engaging in riskier outdoor activities, such as riding of bicycles and scooters, climbing trees or playing sports. The study was led by Dr. Stephen Gwilym whose paper \"hypothesized that there is a place for a committee of safety-conscious, talented writers who could produce high quality books for the purpose of injury prevention,\" noting a potential problem with this strategy: \"Obviously, if children are always in reading books and not outside getting exercise, there is a long-term risk of obesity, rickets and lack of sunlight.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://consumer.healthday.com/general-health-information-16/emergencies-and-first-aid-news-227/harry-potter-books-keep-kids-safe-529859.html | title=Harry Potter Books Keep Kids Safe}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Harry Potter fandom}}\n{{Wikipedia books|Harry Potter}}\n{{Portal|Children and Young Adult Literature}}\n*[[Bartimaeus Sequence]]\n*[[Muggle]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\nWaters, G. Mithrandir, A. (2003). [http://www.goodreads.com/author/show/9830.Galadriel_Waters ''Ultimate Unofficial Guide to the Mysteries of Harry Potter (analysis of Books 1-4)'']. Niles, IL: Wizarding World Press.\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite journal |last1=Karlsson |first1=Marie |last2=Olin-Scheller |first2=Christina |title=\"Let\u00b4s Party!\" Harry Potter fan fiction sites as social settings for narrative gender constructions |journal=[[Gender and Language]] |volume=9 |issue=2 |pages=167&ndash;188 |doi=10.1558/genl.v9i2.17330 |year=2015 |ref=harv }}\n\n{{Fandom}}\n{{Fan fiction}}\n{{Harry Potter}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harry Potter Fandom}}\n[[Category:Harry Potter fandom|Fandom]]\n[[Category:Literary fandom]]\n[[Category:Film and video fandom]]\n", "name_user": "Kind Tennis Fan", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor edit. Paragraphs.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter_fandom"}
{"title_page": "1967 Stanley Cup Finals", "text_new": "{{Infobox Stanley Cup Final\n|year=1967\n|team1='''[[Toronto Maple Leafs]]'''\n|team1_short=Toronto\n|team1_captain=[[George Armstrong (ice hockey)|George Armstrong]]\n|team1_1=2\n|team1_2='''3'''\n|team1_3='''3'''**\n|team1_4=2\n|team1_5='''4'''\n|team1_6='''3'''\n|team1_tot='''4'''\n|team2=[[Montreal Canadiens]]\n|team2_short=Montreal\n|team2_captain=[[Jean Beliveau]]\n|team2_1='''6'''\n|team2_2=0\n|team2_3=2**\n|team2_4='''6'''\n|team2_5=1\n|team2_6=1\n|team2_tot=2\n|gm3_ot=<nowiki>**</nowiki>\n|table-note=<nowiki>*</nowiki> indicates periods of overtime.\n|dates=April 20 \u2013 May 2\n|location1=[[Montreal]]: [[Montreal Forum]] (1, 2, 5)\n|location2=[[Toronto]]: [[Maple Leaf Gardens]] (3, 4, 6)\n|mvp=[[Dave Keon]] (Maple Leafs)\n|series_winner=[[Jim Pappin]] <small>(19:24, second, G6)</small>\n|coaches=Toronto: [[Punch Imlach]]<br />Montreal: [[Toe Blake]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1967 Stanley Cup Finals''' was the [[Stanley Cup Finals|championship series]] of the [[National Hockey League]]'s (NHL) [[1966\u201367 NHL season|1966\u201367 season]], and the culmination of the [[1967 Stanley Cup playoffs]]. A best-of-seven series, it was contested between the [[Montreal Canadiens]] and the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]]. The Maple Leafs won the series, four games to two. In doing so, they won their thirteenth [[Stanley Cup]] championship. To date, this is Toronto's last appearance in the Stanley Cup Finals, and they have [[List of NHL franchise post-season droughts#Stanley Cup droughts|the longest-active championship drought]] in the NHL at 51 (not including [[2004\u201305 NHL season|2004\u201305]] lockout) seasons. The 1967 Stanley Cup Finals was also the last Stanley Cup Finals in the [[Original Six|Original Six Era]]. This was also the last all-Canadian Finals series until [[1986 Stanley Cup Finals|1986]].\n\n==Paths to the Finals==\n{{main|1967 Stanley Cup playoffs}}\nThis was the last Stanley Cup before the 1967 expansion which meant there were only two rounds and three series in total were played in the playoffs. Montreal defeated New York to advance to the finals and Toronto defeated Chicago.\n\n==Game summaries==\nThe average age of the Leafs' players was 31, the oldest lineup to win the Cup.<ref>{{cite book|title=Stanley Cup|pages=42}}</ref> [[Johnny Bower]] was 42 and [[Allan Stanley]] was 41. [[Dave Keon]] won the [[Conn Smythe Trophy]].\n\nMontreal won the opener 6\u20132 Toronto. For the second game, [[Terry Sawchuk]] was replaced with Bower and provided the Leafs with a shutout win, 3\u20130. Bower was in net for game three and won 3\u20132 on [[Bob Pulford]]'s overtime goal. This game has been described as \"one of the most exciting games ever played\".<ref>McFarlane(1973), pg. 171</ref>\n\nBower was injured before game four and Sawchuk had to replace him. [[Al Smith (ice hockey)|Al Smith]] was called up from the minors to serve as back-up for the fourth and fifth games. The Canadiens defeated the Leafs 6\u20132 again, this time in Toronto to even the series. Sawchuk would play well in the next two games, backstopping the Leafs to the Cup.\n\nIn the sixth game Bower returned to the line-up as back up. [[Jim Pappin]] scored his seventh goal of the playoffs and Sawchuk stopped 41 shots helping Toronto win the Cup. Pappin had four goals and four assists in the final series. Captain [[George Armstrong (ice hockey)|George Armstrong]] scored the 3-1 empty-net insurance goal to put game six out of reach.\n\n{{NHLPlayoffs\n|team1=Toronto Maple Leafs\n|team2=Montreal Canadiens\n|stadium1=[[Montreal Forum]]\n|stadium2=[[Maple Leaf Gardens]]\n\n|date1       =April 20\n|home1       =1\n|score1      =2\u20136\n|won1        =2\n|recap1      =www.nhl.com/gamecenter/tor-vs-mtl/1967/04/20/1966030211#game=1966030211,game_state=final\n|1-1-1       =[[Larry Hillman]] (1) - 6:40\n|1-1-2       =6:25 - ''pp'' - [[Yvan Cournoyer]] (1)<br>11:19 - [[Henri Richard]] (1)\n|1-2-1       =[[Jim Pappin]] (4) - ''pp'' - 12:59\n|1-2-2       =5:03 - ''pp'' - [[Yvan Cournoyer]] (2)<br>6:36 - [[Jean Beliveau]] (3)\n|1-3-1       =''No scoring''\n|1-3-2       =4:53 - Henri Richard (2)<br>8:21 - Henri Richard (3)\n|goalie1-1   =[[Terry Sawchuck]], [[Johnny Bower]]\n|goalie1-2   =[[Rogie Vachon]]\n\n|date2       =April 22\n|home2       =1\n|score2      =3\u20130\n|won2        =1\n|recap2      =www.nhl.com/gamecenter/tor-vs-mtl/1967/04/22/1966030212#game=1966030212,game_state=final\n|2-1-1       =[[Pete Stemkowski]] (4) - ''pp'' - 12:14\n|2-1-2       =''No scoring''\n|2-2-1       =[[Mike Walton]] (3) - ''pp'' - 9:12<br>[[Tim Horton]] (2) - 16:57\n|2-2-2       =''No scoring''\n|2-3-1       =''No scoring''\n|2-3-2       =''No scoring''\n|goalie2-1   =[[Johnny Bower]]\n|goalie2-2   =[[Rogie Vachon]]\n\n|date3       =April 25\n|home3       =2\n|score3      =2\u20133\n|ot3         =2\n|won3        =1\n|recap3      =www.nhl.com/gamecenter/mtl-vs-tor/1967/04/25/1966030213#game=1966030213,game_state=final\n|3-1-1       =8:39 - ''pp'' - [[Pete Stemkowski]] (5)\n|3-1-2       =[[Jean Beliveau]] (4) - ''pp'' - 2:27\n|3-2-1       =10:34 - [[Jim Pappin]] (5)\n|3-2-2       =[[John Ferguson, Sr.|John Ferguson]] (4) - 19:10\n|3-3-1       =''No scoring''\n|3-3-2       =''No scoring''\n|3-4-1       =8:26 - [[Bob Pulford]] (1)\n|3-4-2       =''No scoring''\n|goalie3-1   =[[Johnny Bower]]\n|goalie3-2   =[[Rogie Vachon]]\n\n|date4       =April 27\n|home4       =2\n|score4      =6\u20132\n|won4        =2\n|recap4      =www.nhl.com/gamecenter/mtl-vs-tor/1967/04/27/1966030214#game=1966030214,game_state=final\n|4-1-1       =''No scoring''\n|4-1-2       =[[Ralph Backstrom]] (4) - 12:25<br>[[Jean Beliveau]] (5) - ''pp'' - 13:08\n|4-2-1       =2:09 - ''pp'' - [[Mike Walton]] (4)<br>12:16 - [[Tim Horton]] (3)\n|4-2-2       =[[Henri Richard]] (4) - 2:26<br>Jean Beliveau (6) - 13:41<br>Ralph Backstrom (5) - 15:58\n|4-3-1       =''No scoring''\n|4-3-2       =[[Jim Roberts (ice hockey, born 1940)|Jimmy Roberts]] (1) - 15:17\n|goalie4-1   =[[Terry Sawchuk]]\n|goalie4-2   =[[Rogie Vachon]]\n\n|date5       =April 29\n|home5       =1\n|score5      =4\u20131\n|won5        =1\n|recap5      =www.nhl.com/gamecenter/tor-vs-mtl/1967/04/29/1966030215#game=1966030215,game_state=final\n|5-1-1       =[[Jim Pappin]] (6) - ''pp'' - 15:06\n|5-1-2       =6:03 - [[Leon Rochefort]] (1)\n|5-2-1       =[[Brian Conacher]] (3) - 3:07<br>[[Marcel Pronovost]] (1) - ''sh'' - 12:02<br>[[Dave Keon]] (3) - 19:27\n|5-2-2       =''No scoring''\n|5-3-1       =''No scoring''\n|5-3-2       =''No scoring''\n|goalie5-1   =[[Terry Sawchuk]]\n|goalie5-2   =[[Rogie Vachon]], [[Gump Worsley]]\n\n|date6       =May 2\n|home6       =2\n|score6      =1\u20133\n|won6        =1\n|recap6      =www.nhl.com/gamecenter/mtl-vs-tor/1967/05/02/1966030216#game=1966030216,game_state=final\n|6-1-1       =''No scoring''\n|6-1-2       =''No scoring''\n|6-2-1       =6:25 - [[Ron Ellis]] (2)<br>19:24 - [[Jim Pappin]] (7)\n|6-2-2       =''No scoring''\n|6-3-1       =19:13 - [[George Armstrong (ice hockey)|George Armstrong]] (2)\n|6-3-2       =[[Dick Duff]] (2) - 5:28\n|goalie6-1   =[[Terry Sawchuk]]\n|goalie6-2   =[[Gump Worsley]]\n\n|series      =Toronto won series 4\u20132\n}}\n\n==Toronto Maple Leafs 1967 Stanley Cup champions==\n{{Stanley Cup champion\n|goaltenders=*30 [[Terry Sawchuk]]\n*1 [[Johnny Bower]]\n*1 [[Al Smith (ice hockey)|Al Smith]]\u2020\u2020 \n|defence=*2 [[Larry Hillman]]\n*3 [[Marcel Pronovost]]\n*7 Miles [[Tim Horton]]\n*21 [[Bob Baun]]\n*24 [[Aut Erickson]]\u2020\u2020\u2020    \n*26 [[Allan Stanley]] (A)\n|centers=*4 Leonard [[Red Kelly]] \n*12 [[Pete Stemkowski]]\n*14 [[Dave Keon]]\n*16 [[Mike Walton]]\n*22 [[Brian Conacher]]\n*25 [[Milan Marcetta]]\u2020\u2020\u2020    \n|wingers=*8 [[Ron Ellis]]\n*10 [[George Armstrong (ice hockey)|George Armstrong]] (Captain)\n*15 [[Larry Jeffrey]]\n*18 [[Jim Pappin]]\n*20 [[Bob Pulford]] (A)\n*23 [[Eddie Shack]] \n*27 [[Frank Mahovlich]]\n|non-players=\n* [[Stafford Smythe]] (President/Owner), [[Harold Ballard]] (Exe. Vice President/Owner) \n*[[John Bassett]] (Chairman/Owner), George [[Punch Imlach]] (Manager-Coach)\n* Frank [[King Clancy]] (Asst. Manager-Coach), [[Bob Davidson (hockey)|Bob Davidson]] (Chief Scout)\n* John Anderson (Business Manager)\n* Bob Haggert (Trainer), Tom Nayler (Asst. Trainer)\n* Dr. Karl Elieff (Physiotherapist)\n* Richard Smythe (Mascot)\n\n|engraving-notes=\n* The first \"K\" in Peter Stemkowski's name was engraved backwards.\n* Stafford Smythe's name was misspelled  C. ST FFORD SMYTHE PRESIDENT missing an \"A\". Both mistakes were corrected on the Replica Cup created in 1992\u201393.\n* Leonard \"Red\" Kelly won 8 Stanley Cups.  He was engraved as Leonard Kelly in 1954, 1955, 1962, 1963, 1964.  Kelly was engraved as Red Kelly in 1950, 1952, 1967.\n*\u2020\u2020\u2020 Milan Marcetta, played 3 games in the finals and Aut Erickson played 1 game in the finals qualifying to be on the cup.  Neither player played a game for Toronto in regular season.\n* \u2020\u2020Johnny Bower was 42 years old when he won his fourth and final Stanley Cup. Bower missed 2 games in the finals with an injury. Al Smith was dressed in his place. Smith's name was left off the Cup, because he only played 1 regular season game, and did not play in the playoffs.  Al Smith qualified to be on the Cup, because he was dressed in the finals. \n* \u2020 #19 Kent Douglas (defense), and #24 John Brenneman (winger) were sent to the minors before the trading deadline.  They played half regular season games, qualified to win the Cup, but name was left off for playing in minors during the playoffs.\n* Dr. Hugh Symthe (Team Physician) - Also left (His name is on cup 1942 with Toronto as mascot). \n|\n}}\n\n===Won all 4 Stanley Cups in 6 Years with Toronto 1962, 1963, 1964, 1967===\nGeorge Armstrong, Bob Baun, Johnny Bower, Larry Hillman, Tim Horton, Red Kelly, Dave Keon, Frank Mahovlich, Bob Pulford, Eddie Shack, Allan Stanley (11 players), Stafford Smythe, Harold Ballard, John Bassett, Punch Imlach, King Clancy, Bob Haggert, Tom Nayler (7 non-players), Bob Davidson, Karl Elieff (were part of all 4 cups, but were not included on the cup each season.)\n\n==See also==\n* [[1966\u201367 NHL season]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{external media|video1={{youtube|1Pyap77uGSU|1967 Stanley Cup Final, Game 6: Maple Leafs vs. Canadiens}}}}\n*{{cite web | url=http://www.nhl.com/info/all-time-nhl-playoff-results|title=All-Time NHL Results}}\n* {{cite book|editor=Diamond, Dan |title=Total Stanley Cup|year=2000|publisher=NHL}}\n*{{cite book |title=The History of the National Hockey League |last=McFarlane |first=Brian |year=1973 |publisher=Charles Scribner's Sons |location=New York |isbn=0-684-13424-1 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/storyofnationalh0000mcfa }}\n* {{cite book |author=Podnieks, Andrew |author2=Hockey Hall of Fame |year=2004 |title=Lord Stanley's Cup |publisher=Triumph Books |isbn=978-1-55168-261-7}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box |\n  before = [[1966 Stanley Cup Finals|Montreal Canadiens<br />1966]] |\n  after = [[1968 Stanley Cup Finals|Montreal Canadiens <br />1968]] |\n  title = [[List of Stanley Cup champions|Toronto Maple Leafs <br />Stanley Cup Champions]] |\n  years = 1967|\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Navboxes|\nlist1=\n{{Stanley Cup Finals}}\n{{1966\u201367 NHL season by team}} \n{{Montreal Canadiens}}\n{{Toronto Maple Leafs}}\n{{NHL on CBS}}\n{{Hockey Night in Canada}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:1967 Stanley Cup| ]]\n[[Category:1966\u201367 NHL season|Stanley Cup]]\n[[Category:Montreal Canadiens games]]\n[[Category:Toronto Maple Leafs games]]\n[[Category:Stanley Cup Finals]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Montreal]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Toronto]]\n[[Category:April 1967 sports events|Stanley Cup]]\n[[Category:May 1967 sports events|Stanley Cup]]\n[[Category:1960s in Montreal]]\n[[Category:1967 in Quebec|Stanley Cup]]\n[[Category:1967 in Toronto|Stanley Cup]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Stanley Cup Final\n|year=1967\n|team1='''[[Toronto Maple Leafs]]'''\n|team1_short=Toronto\n|team1_captain=[[George Armstrong (ice hockey)|George Armstrong]]\n|team1_1=2\n|team1_2='''3'''\n|team1_3='''3'''**\n|team1_4=2\n|team1_5='''4'''\n|team1_6='''3'''\n|team1_tot='''4'''\n|team2=[[Montreal Canadiens]]\n|team2_short=Montreal\n|team2_captain=[[Jean Beliveau]]\n|team2_1='''6'''\n|team2_2=0\n|team2_3=2**\n|team2_4='''6'''\n|team2_5=1\n|team2_6=1\n|team2_tot=2\n|gm3_ot=<nowiki>**</nowiki>\n|table-note=<nowiki>*</nowiki> indicates periods of overtime.\n|dates=April 20 \u2013 May 2\n|location1=[[Montreal]]: [[Montreal Forum]] (1, 2, 5)\n|location2=[[Toronto]]: [[Maple Leaf Gardens]] (3, 4, 6)\n|mvp=[[Dave Keon]] (Maple Leafs)\n|series_winner=[[Jim Pappin]] <small>(19:24, second, G6)</small>\n|coaches=Toronto: [[Punch Imlach]]<br />Montreal: [[Toe Blake]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1967 Stanley Cup Finals''' was the [[Stanley Cup Finals|championship series]] of the [[National Hockey League]]'s (NHL) [[1966\u201367 NHL season|1966\u201367 season]], and the culmination of the [[1967 Stanley Cup playoffs]]. A best-of-seven series, it was contested between the [[Montreal Canadiens]] and the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]]. The Maple Leafs won the series, four games to two. In doing so, they won their thirteenth [[Stanley Cup]] championship. To date, this is Toronto's last appearance in the Stanley Cup Finals, and they have [[List of NHL franchise post-season droughts#Stanley Cup droughts|the longest-active championship drought]] in the NHL at 51 (not including [[2004\u201305 NHL season|2004\u201305]] lockout) seasons. The 1967 Stanley Cup Finals was also the last Stanley Cup Finals in the [[Original Six|Original Six Era]]. This was also the last all-Canadian Finals series until [[1986 Stanley Cup Finals|1986]].\n\n==Paths to the Finals==\n{{main|1967 Stanley Cup playoffs}}\nThis was the last Stanley Cup before the 1967 expansion which meant there were only two rounds and three series in total were played in the playoffs. Montreal defeated New York to advance to the finals and Toronto defeated Chicago.\n\n==Game summaries==\nThe average age of the Leafs' players was 31, the oldest lineup to win the Cup.<ref>{{cite book|title=Stanley Cup|pages=42}}</ref> [[Johnny Bower]] was 42 and [[Allan Stanley]] was 41. [[Dave Keon]] won the [[Conn Smythe Trophy]].\n\nMontreal won the opener 6\u20132 Toronto. For the second game, [[Terry Sawchuk]] was replaced with Bower and provided the Leafs with a shutout win, 3\u20130. Bower was in net for game three and won 3\u20132 on [[Bob Pulford]]'s overtime goal. This game has been described as \"one of the most exciting games ever played\".<ref>McFarlane(1973), pg. 171</ref>\n\nBower was injured before game four and Sawchuk had to replace him. [[Al Smith (ice hockey)|Al Smith]] was called up from the minors to serve as back-up for the fourth and fifth games. The Canadiens defeated the Leafs 6\u20132 again, this time in Toronto to even the series. Sawchuk would play well in the next two games, backstopping the Leafs to the Cup.\n\nIn the sixth game Bower returned to the line-up as back up. [[Jim Pappin]] scored his seventh goal of the playoffs and Sawchuk stopped 41 shots helping Toronto win the Cup. Pappin had four goals and four assists in the final series. Captain [[George Armstrong (ice hockey)|George Armstrong]] scored the 3-1 empty-net insurance goal to put game six out of reach.\n\n{{NHLPlayoffs\n|team1=Toronto Maple Leafs\n|team2=Montreal Canadiens\n|stadium1=[[Montreal Forum]]\n|stadium2=[[Maple Leaf Gardens]]\n\n|date1       =April 20\n|home1       =1\n|score1      =2\u20136\n|won1        =2\n|recap1      =www.nhl.com/gamecenter/tor-vs-mtl/1967/04/20/1966030211#game=1966030211,game_state=final\n|1-1-1       =[[Larry Hillman]] (1) - 6:40\n|1-1-2       =6:25 - ''pp'' - [[Yvan Cournoyer]] (1)<br>11:19 - [[Henri Richard]] (1)\n|1-2-1       =[[Jim Pappin]] (4) - ''pp'' - 12:59\n|1-2-2       